






Version 11 --- June 2026

- *Tick-Borne Infections --- Babesia Evidence Update (Breitschwerdt 2025)* ([Chapter 7, updated `@lim:babesia-evidence-gap`, new `@spec:babesia-hemolysis-haptoglobin` (cert 0.18), new `@oq:babesia-falsification`, new `@oq:babesia-research-priorities` (5 Tier 1 research proposals: serosurvey+CPET, Hp/LDH screening, ODE model, RBC deformability biomarker, diagnostic equity); hypothesis registry, 3 new entries; `bib/immune.bib`, 7 new entries; Appendix H, 7 new entries; retroactive ch07 main-file duplicate-paragraph update; `ops/plans/babesia-50pct-mecfs-integration-plan.md`; subtree 14 nodes (9 integrated, 5 parked)]): The "50% Babesia in ME patients" claim is based on Breitschwerdt 2025 (n=50, no controls) finding 24% Babesia PCR, 46% combined Babesia+Bartonella --- the circulating claim conflates the combined rate with Babesia alone. The paper's 95% CI (12--36%) overlaps background seroprevalence in endemic areas; the sole controlled comparison (MacDonald 1996) was null. A speculative haptoglobin-depletion pathway connects Babesia-induced hemolysis to documented ME/CFS biochemistry (Moezzi 2025), and a null-hypothesis framework outlines what would reject the null. Five research proposals (serosurvey+CPET, Hp/LDH screening triage, ODE modeling, ektacytometry biomarker, diagnostic equity program) complete the chapter with concrete next steps. Adversarial review: CI-overlap and MacDonald directional issues addressed; falsification thresholds recast as illustrative. PROCEED; clinical relevance MEDIUM. _Motivated by:_ Breitschwerdt 2025 @Breitschwerdt2025BabesiaCFS --- widely-circulated patient-community finding requiring contextualization.

- *Tick-Borne Infections × ME/CFS Symptom Domains (2024–2026 update)* ([Chapter 7, new subsection "Symptom-Domain-Specific Findings (2024–2026)" in the tick-borne section `@sec:tick-borne`: `@obs:lyme-fatigue-persistence`, `@spec:hla-shared-susceptibility` (cert 0.30), `@lim:babesia-evidence-gap`, plus a `#clinical-finding` on PTLD T-cell subsets (cert 0.55) and a `#practical-warning` on disulfiram; hypothesis registry, 1 new speculation; `bib/immune.bib`, 11 new entries with `research_stream=tick-borne-symptom-domains`; Appendix H, 11 new annotated entries]): Maps recent tick-borne evidence to specific ME/CFS symptom domains rather than treating each pathogen in isolation. Fatigue is the single post-Lyme symptom domain that persists beyond 12 months in CDC population data (Nawrocki 2025, n=146k); the first PTLD T-cell immunophenotyping shows symptom-domain-specific immune signatures paralleling ME/CFS (Girgis 2025, AUC 0.83 on a small control arm); an in-silico HLA-binding hypothesis proposes shared genetic susceptibility across ME/CFS, PTLDS, and Long COVID (Georgopoulos 2025, cert 0.30, flagged as possibly a computational artifact); a controlled tilt-table study confirms Lyme/CFS autonomic overlap (Milovanovic 2025); a neurobartonellosis framework and CNS-infection cohort deepen the Bartonella–cognition link (Bush 2024, Yakubovsky 2026); VlsE isotyping and CSF epitope profiling offer routes to stage active vs resolved infection (Nair 2025, Marques 2026); and a disulfiram pilot is flagged research-stage-only for a neuropathy harm signal (Kuvaldina 2025). _Babesia_ remains the least-studied of the three in an ME/CFS context. Integration decision: PROCEED; clinical relevance MEDIUM (mechanistic/diagnostic context, no new actionable treatment). _Motivated by:_ Nawrocki 2025 @Nawrocki2025LymeSymptomsCDC — CDC population data isolating fatigue as the persistent post-Lyme domain gave a symptom-domain-specific reason to update coverage that previously treated tick-borne illness pathogen-by-pathogen rather than symptom-by-symptom.

- *Tick-Borne Infections × ME/CFS — Mechanistic Bridges and Convergence (Phase 4–7 brainstorm follow-on)* ([Chapter 7, new `@spec:tickborne-kynurenine-fatigue` (cert 0.28), `@spec:tickborne-combinatorial-immune` (cert 0.35), `@spec:bartonella-endothelial-microclot` (cert 0.22), `@lim:ptlds-overlap-definitional`, `@syn:tickborne-symptom-domain-model`; Chapter 35, PTLDS shared-mechanisms bullets reinforced with 3 citation additions (@Girgis2025PTLDTcell for T-cell data, @Milovanovic2025LymeHUT for autonomic, @Nawrocki2025LymeSymptomsCDC for fatigue-domain specificity — citation-only, no certainty shifts); hypothesis registry, 3 new speculations; `ops/brainstorms/`, 44 ideas generated across all 12 categories (3 Tier 1 bridges integrated, remainder tree-only/deduplicated/covered); `ops/plans/hypotheses-trees/subtrees/tick-borne-symptom-domains.md`, 44 nodes; Phase 7: 0 certainty bumps (all new specs below concurrent-cycle bump thresholds), 1 contingency annotation (`spec:tickborne-kynurenine-fatigue` contingent on `hyp:peripheral-serotonin-convergence` cert 0.60)]): Brainstorm-driven Phase 4–7 follow-on bridging tick-borne evidence to the paper's existing ME/CFS mechanisms. Three bridge speculations: the kynurenine shunt as a route from sustained IFN-γ→IDO activation to the peripheral serotonin depletion model (ch13); combinatorial immune signatures as an explanation for cross-study inconsistency in ME/CFS immunophenotyping — single markers fail but multi-parameter classifiers recover signal (ch07); and _Bartonella_ endotheliotropism as a non-autoantibody route to the microclot pathology developed for ME/CFS and Long COVID (ch10). Adds a definitional caveat: the 26/29 PTLDS–ME/CFS symptom overlap may partly reflect how both syndromes are constructed from the same core symptoms, not shared biology. Section capped with a `#synthesis` environment condensing the convergent model. Retroactive reinforcement for the existing ch35 PTLDS shared-mechanisms bullets (Girgis 2025 T