- *Herpesvirus Antibody Persistence — Long-Lived Plasma Cell Biology and the Constraints on Herpesvirus Serology Interpretation in ME/CFS* ([Chapter 7, new `subsec-06-antibody-persistence` with foundational LLPC immunology, interpretive serology table (with VCA IgM reactivation possibility and qPCR/ALR caveat), open-question on universal elevation (`@oq:herpesvirus-antibody-universal`), LSR diagnostic biomarker hypothesis (`@hyp:lytic-structural-igg-ratio`, certainty 0.45, Origin: brainstorm, with explicit caveats about single-group dUTPase data dependency and lack of mechanistic basis for lytic-only boosting), speculation on B cell dysregulation as driver (`@spec:antibody-elevation-bcell-dysregulation`), limitations on antibody interpretation (`@lim:herpesvirus-antibody-interpretation` — acknowledges reactivation can boost structural IgG, e.g. VZV during shingles, and includes pragmatic clinical guidance for time-limited antiviral trial when confirmatory testing unavailable) and methodological weaknesses (`@lim:herpesvirus-serology-methods` — symmetrical critique of both positive and null studies), convergent synthesis (`@syn:herpesvirus-antibody-persistence-model`); retroactive caveat additions to ch03, ch04, ch05 cross-referencing antibody persistence section; hypothesis registry, 4 new entries; `bib/immune.bib`, 9 new entries; `bib/viral-infection.bib`, 11 new entries; Appendix H, 15 new annotated entries; brainstorm 22 ideas, 1 Tier 1 integrated (LSR), critical categories consolidated into methodological limitation; adversarial review: 21 CRITICAL/HIGH findings across 6 personas addressed — central claim softened (structural IgG CAN be boosted by reactivation), qPCR/ALR paradox resolved, VCA IgM reactivation possibility added, pragmatic clinical algorithm included, methodological critique symmetrised, LSR caveats substantively strengthened]): The persistence of herpesvirus antibodies decades after primary infection reflects a dominant long-lived plasma cell (LLPC) antigen-independent baseline — but this baseline is not the whole story. Structural antigen IgG CAN rise during clinical reactivation (VZV/shingles, CMV disease), so isolated titre elevation is ambiguous rather than categorically uninformative. The correct interpretive principle: structural IgG has a large antigen-independent LLPC component, and elevated titres alone, without corroborating lytic-cycle antibody or viral nucleic acid data, are insufficient to diagnose active reactivation. When confirmatory testing is negative or unavailable, a time-limited antiviral trial with predefined stopping rules and symptom tracking remains a reasonable shared-decision option for the post-infectious subset — consistent with the two controlled positive trials (Lerner 2007, Montoya 2013) that enrolled on elevated titres. Clinical relevance: MEDIUM (constrains serological interpretation; provides clinical decision framework). Quality note: BLOAT flag noted but justified by essential immunology education content. _Motivated by:_ @Amanna2007Duration @Hammarlund2017PlasmaCell — the foundational demonstration that antiviral antibodies are maintained antigen-independently, constraining — but not eliminating — the interpretive value of herpesvirus serology in ME/CFS.

- *Inadequate Treatment Duration as a Systematic Confound in Negative Chronic Disease Trials: The Lyme Paradigm Applied to ME/CFS* ([Chapter 31, negative-trials section: enhanced acyclovir lesson (co-infection spectrum gap), enhanced valganciclovir lesson (duration-response from Watt 2012, $p=0.0002$), new cross-cutting lesson bullet (treatment duration/intensity as systematic confound with three-part framework), new `@sec:lyme-paradigm` (certainty 0.65), new `@lim:duration-caveats` (six limitations, including selection-bias, placebo confound, natural-recovery contamination, retrospective evidence, and unfalsifiability risk), new `@oq:duration-critique-research` (four testable research directions); hypothesis registry, 3 new entries; `bib/treatments.bib`, 14 new entries; `bib/viral-infection.bib`, 1 new entry; Appendix H, 15 new annotated entries; brainstorm 38 ideas across all 12 categories, 4 Tier 1 integrated, critical categories (cats 10-12) fully integrated as self-critique; removed duplicate `#include` of negative-trials from synthesis-and-meta-analyses to fix label duplication]): The Lyme disease treatment literature provides a paradigmatic case study in how trial design choices can produce false-negative conclusions: Klempner et al. (2001) found "no benefit" to 90-day antibiotics, but DeLong (2012) showed all four retreatment RCTs were underpowered, two showing significant benefit on individual endpoints; enrolled patients averaged 4.7yr illness with 3+ prior failed courses; Borrelia forms persister/biofilm variants requiring combination therapy (Feng 2019); and standard regimens do not cover co-infections such as Babesia and Bartonella (Popov 2026). Extended to ME/CFS: Watt (2012) found longer valganciclovir predicted better response ($p=0.0002$), Fluge (2015) reported 23-week mean response lag, Strayer (2020) found a 2--8yr disease-duration treatment window. The three-part framework — (1) adequate duration, (2) broad enough spectrum/coverage, (3) patients within treatment window — provides a structured way to interrogate negative trial results before accepting them as evidence of inefficacy, while acknowledging that trials like RituxME (Fluge 2019, adequately-powered 12-month Phase III) are genuinely definitive negatives. Clinical relevance: MEDIUM (methodological framework, not a treatment recommendation; affects interpretation of existing trial evidence). _Motivated by:_ @Klempner2001LymeAbx @DeLong2012AbxRetreat @Watt2012ValganciclovirResponse — the Lyme retreatment controversy and the duration-response gradient in ME/CFS antiviral therapy.

- *VMAT2 Striatal Dopaminergic Terminal Loss in Long COVID — Cross-Condition Evidence for Dopaminergic Deficiency in Post-Infectious Neuropsychiatric Symptoms* ([Chapter 8, new `@cf:vmat2-longcovid`, `@oq:vmat2-generalizability`, `@spec:da-atp-double-hit`, `@spec:motivation-trap`, `@obs:ifna-da-model`, `@lim:vmat2-evidence-quality`, `@syn:vmat2-dopaminergic-convergence`; retroactive xrefs to `@spec:vesicular-ne-deficiency`, `@ach:catecholamine-deficit`, `@spec:adhd-dopamine-nrf2-nlrp3`; Chapter 24, new `@subsec:dopaminergic-augmentation` with `@spec:dopaminergic-augmentation-mecfs` (trial framework, cert 0.25) and `@warn:dopaminergic-augmentation-safety`; hypothesis registry +2; bib 13 entries; brainstorm 63 ideas, Phase 5 triage: 5 Tier 1 integrated, critical categories consolidated; adversarial review: 10 critical items fixed — PD comparison recalibrated with threshold context, \(\Delta\)pH reframed as genuine ambiguity, certainties reduced to match evidence, Aregawi constraint stated as unresolved inconsistency, "convergent" corrected to "co-occurring" for single-cohort data, treatment section recast as trial framework]): Liu YK et al. (2026, eBioMedicine, n=24 long COVID vs 24 controls) — first direct PET evidence of postviral striatal dopaminergic terminal loss. Integration: PROCEED. Key unresolved inconsistency: Aregawi 2026 normal CSF DA pathway in PI-ME/CFS — simultaneous CSF+PET measurement required.

- *Hypothalamic CRH-Neuron Depletion — Central Origin of ME/CFS Hypocortisolism (Brain Autopsy)* ([Chapter 9, HPA-axis "Mechanisms of HPA Dysfunction" subsection: new "Central CRH-Neuron Loss in the Hypothalamus" block `sec:central-crh-loss` with two speculation environments (`@spec:central-crh-loss`, `@spec:crh-cell-type-specificity`), two open-question environments (`@oq:crh-loss-driver`, `@oq:crh-loss-experiments`), one further low-certainty speculation (`@spec:crh-loss-trigger-autoimmune`), one speculation on downstream symptom predictions (`@spec:crh-loss-downstream-symptoms`), and a preliminary/severity-restricted limitation; HPA-axis "Abnormalities" subsection: pre-existing `@cf:crh-neuron-depletion` reconciled from `#clinical-finding` to `#observation` and re-pointed from `@HealthRising2025` to the proper primary key `@dasilva2025iacfscrh`; Chapter 14d cross-disease hub: corrected a certainty-inflation reference to `@cf:crh-neuron-depletion` (0.55 → 0.30); bib, 11 new entries in `endocrine-reproductive.bib` and `neuroinflammation.bib`; Appendix H, 9 new annotated entries; hypothesis registry, 6 new entries]): Integrates the preliminary brain-autopsy finding (Da Silva et al., University of Amsterdam / Netherlands Brain Bank ME/CFS programme, presented at IACFS/ME 2025) of dramatically reduced CRH-immunoreactive neurons in the hypothalamic paraventricular nucleus of seven severe deceased ME/CFS patients, with vasopressin/oxytocin neurons preserved and downstream pituitary receptor/POMC downregulation. Key significance: if replicated, this relocates the long-documented ME/CFS hypocortisolism from the adrenal gland to a central hypothalamic manufacturing deficit, and the reported *direction* (CRH reduced) is opposite to the CRH *increase* seen in depression and MS by the same brain-bank methodology — a potential neuroanatomical distinction from psychiatric illness. Integrated conservatively as speculation/open-question/limitation only (Phase 2 decision: PARTIAL) because the source is a single non-peer-reviewed conference presentation (n=7, unpublished, no replication, certainty 0.30); every claim carries explicit certainty (0.10–0.30), a "Refuted if" clause, and caveats spanning the peptide-depletion-versus-cell-death confound, end-stage/agonal/polypharmacy confounds, unblinded quantification, and severity restriction (severe/very-severe only; mild/moderate unknown). No treatment recommendation: the cortisol-replacement caution is framed as mechanistic only. Quality note: WEAK-EVIDENCE — the evidence base is preliminary; clinical relevance MEDIUM. Adversarial review converged (0 CRITICAL, 0 HIGH after fixes). _Motivated by:_ Da Silva et al. IACFS/ME 2025 @dasilva2025iacfscrh (the reported CRH-neuron depletion), with the direction-reversal contrast anchored by @raadsheer1994crh and @purba1995crhms and the cell-type-specific post-infectious precedent by @sauve2023gnrh.

- *Retroactive High-Level Syntheses (Phase 10a), Part 2 — HIF-2$alpha$ Endothelial and HIF-1$alpha$ Pathway-Inertia Mechanisms* ([Chapter 10, new `@syn:hif2a-endothelial-mechanism-model` in the endothelial-dysfunction subsection, condensing the four HIF-2$alpha$ environments (`@hyp:hif2a-sustained-postviral`, `@spec:hif2a-beta2ar-negative`, `@spec:hif2a-microclot-vwf`, `@spec:nrf2-exhaustion-hif2a`) into a sustained-HIF-2$alpha$ endothelial-barrier mechanism — the $beta$2AR-autoantibody-negative subtype, the vWF/microclot linkage, and NRF2 exhaustion as permissive brake-loss — with the belzutifan/darunavir therapeutic corollary; Chapter 14k, new `@syn:hif1a-pathway-inertia-model` condensing the HIF-1$alpha$ environments (`@spec:hif-pathway-inertia`, `@spec:altitude-paradox`, `@spec:pem-hif-maladaptation`, `@hyp:hif1alpha-mito-ecm-triad`, `@hyp:hif1alpha-connective-tissue`, `@spec:butyrate-hif1a`) into a HIF-1$alpha$ adaptive-failure model with two discriminable failure modes (blunted induction vs failed de-activation) and its retraining-oriented interventions (intermittent hypoxic training, breathing retraining, HIF-PH inhibitors with stratification caution)]): Completes the two remaining Phase 10a-eligible integrations from the vagal cycle's retroactive-synthesis scan. Written as *two separate mechanism-specific syntheses* rather than one combined HIF synthesis, because HIF-1$alpha$ (adaptive-failure / altitude / PEM-hibernation / ECM) and HIF-2$alpha$ (sustained endothelial activation / microclot / therapeutic-stratification) are distinct molecular mechanisms with distinct primary chapters and treatment implications; merging would blur two causal stories. Both explicitly defer the VEGF/angiogenic-failure and sFlt-1/PlGF intersection to the pre-existing `@syn:vegf-pathway-convergence` (Chapter 14d) rather than duplicating it. Each keeps its evidence base honest (HIF-2$alpha$ chain is in-vitro spike-stimulated-endothelial-cell inference, never measured in ME/CFS; HIF-1$alpha$ inertia rests on tendinopathy/altitude analogy with no post-exertional HIF time-course study) and closes with the single decisive experiment (endothelial HIF-2$alpha$ status study; post-CPET HIF-1$alpha$ transcriptional time-course). No new claims, citations, or certainties — pure condensation of already-integrated, already-reviewed environments; adversarial + Typst review CLEAN (0 findings). _Motivated by:_ Phase 10a detection during the vagal-gastric-denervation cycle; @Ribeiro2026HIF2alpha and @Kaczmarek2023miRNAhypoxia anchor the two respective mechanisms.

- *Retroactive High-Level Syntheses (Phase 10a) — Brain-First Genetic Architecture and Brain Clearance Architecture* ([Chapter 12, new `@syn:brain-first-glutamatergic-genetic-architecture` condensing ~20 GWAS/DecodeME/Maccallini environments (brain-only tissue enrichment, glutamatergic-synapse replication, two-hit model, cerebellar CCAS grounding, depression paradox, dopaminergic effort-valuation signal, and the polygenic-subtyping proposals) that were scattered across ch12, ch14d, ch14h, and ch16 with no unifying synthesis; Chapter 15, new `@syn:brain-clearance-architecture-model` condensing ~19 brain-clearance environments (Chayama 2026 nearest-exit architecture, Toscano 2026 dual-speed glymphatics, inflammatory-rerouting-vs-obstructive-trapping failure modes, orexin–vasomotion loop, PEM ratchet, skull-border B-cell tolerance, CSF:blood-ratio and skull-channel biomarkers) into a single architectural framework, distinct from and broader than the pre-existing tau-only `@syn:tau-glymphatic-convergence`]): Two completed integrations had accumulated ≥3 environments across ≥2 chapters without a `#synthesis` surfacing their convergent argument (the Phase 10a trigger). Each synthesis states what the evidence collectively supports, keeps the constructive themes and hard constraints in explicit balance (both note the animal-model / no-direct-ME/CFS-data limits — the genetics is a preprint with modest $h^2_("SNP") approx 0.095$; the clearance mechanisms are rodent-derived and never imaged in ME/CFS), and closes with the single most decisive experiment (cell-type-stratified polygenic subtyping validation; direct glymphatic imaging with paired CSF:blood neuronal-protein measurement). No new claims, citations, or certainties were introduced — these are pure condensations of already-integrated, already-reviewed environments. _Motivated by:_ Phase 10a retroactive-synthesis detection run at user request during the vagal-gastric-denervation cycle; @Maccallini2026metaGWAS and @Chayama2026BrainClearance anchor the two respective frameworks.


- *Vagal Cholinergic Gastric Denervation in Long COVID — Structural Substrate for Dysautonomia and a Two-Route CAP-Disengagement Model* ([Chapter 10, new `@ach:vagal-structural-denervation` (a clinical-finding environment, cert 0.45, single unreplicated study) in the post-COVID cardiovascular section presenting Acanfora's in vivo gastric-mucosal cholinergic denervation finding as preliminary, plus a qualifier added to the `@sec:hrv` Ryabkova structural-vs-functional discussion; Chapter 8, new `@sec:sfn-visceral-somatic` subsection and `@oq:sfn-visceral-vs-somatic` on the visceral-vs-somatic small-fiber distinction (Acanfora visceral vs Oaklander/Azcue somatic), plus a Woo citation on viral vagal damage; Chapter 13, new `@hyp:structural-vagal-denervation-cap` (cert 0.35) proposing structural cholinergic denervation as a route to cholinergic-anti-inflammatory-pathway disengagement distinct from and complementary to the existing functional GPCR-autoantibody blockade `@spec:cap-autoantibody-blockade` (with a super-additive two-hit prediction), `@lim:vagal-enteric-deconditioning` consolidating five critical threats (vagal-vs-enteric ambiguity, deconditioning confound, small-n winner's curse, dyspeptic-control confound, functional-route redundancy), `@spec:vstr-dag-node` (cert 0.20) proposing a structural-capacity variable $V_(upright("str"))$ as a distinct causal-DAG node, and `@syn:vagal-structural-functional-axis` synthesising the model; reinforcement citations added to Chapter 17 (impaired-vagal-tone bullet: Tracey + Acanfora), Chapter 14i (Vagus→Immune bullet: Tracey), and Chapter 11 (gut-vagal bullets: Woo, Tracey, Bonaz); `bib/autonomic-cardiovascular.bib`, 7 new entries with `research_stream=vagal-gastric-denervation-longcovid` (duplicate `azcue2023dysautonomiasfn` removed — the paper was already present as `Azcue2023sfn`); Appendix H, 8 new annotated entries (1 Azcue duplicate consolidated); hypothesis registry, 4 new entries (hyp, oq, spec:vstr, lim)]): Acanfora et al.\ (2026, Int J Infect Dis, PMID 42425362; n=12 Long COVID vs 8 dyspeptic controls) provide the first in vivo morphological evidence of *selective visceral* cholinergic (VIP+) gastric-mucosal denervation, with skin nerve density preserved, correlating with vagal HRV (LF/HF $R=0.50$), NT-proBNP ($R=0.52$), and D-dimer ($R=0.61$). This supplies a *structural* substrate for post-viral dysautonomia distinct from the paper's existing *functional* autoantibody CAP-blockade model, and — via the well-established cholinergic anti-inflammatory pathway (Tracey 2002, Bonaz 2018) plus vagus-nerve viral inflammation (Woo 2023) and ultrasound thickening (Lladós 2024) — a coherent structural→CAP-disengagement→inflammation chain. Clinical relevance: MEDIUM (mechanistic context and vagus-nerve-stimulation rationale only; no ME/CFS-specific efficacy or safety data; VNS framed throughout as investigational, not a recommendation). All direct evidence is Long-COVID-specific: no ME/CFS gastric histology exists, ME/CFS instead shows somatic (not visceral) small-fiber neuropathy, and the founding study cannot distinguish vagal from enteric fibers, is uncontrolled for deconditioning, and rests on 12 patients — so the ME/CFS extrapolation is explicitly a hypothesis awaiting a decisive paired-biopsy study, not an established mechanism. _Motivated by:_ @acanfora2026vagaldenervation — first in vivo structural vagal cholinergic denervation in post-viral illness; @woo2023vagusinflammation — SARS-CoV-2 RNA and monocyte infiltration within the vagus nerve provides the proximal mechanism; @tracey2002inflammatoryreflex — the cholinergic anti-inflammatory pathway linking vagal efferent loss to sustained inflammation.

- *Ocular Sjögren / ME/CFS Overlap — the Ocular Surface as a Candidate Neuro-Immune Window, a Non-Autoimmune Sicca Mechanism, and Its Confounds* ([Chapter 14d, extending the existing Sjögren's cross-disease block: new `@spec:ocular-surface-neuroimmune-window` (cert 0.25) proposing the tear-film inflammatory-cytokine + corneal subbasal C-fiber axis as a shared readout, `@oq:mecfs-tear-proteome` asking whether the ME/CFS tear proteome resembles the Sjögren's signature, `@spec:mecfs-lacrimal-denervation` (cert 0.28) proposing functional parasympathetic denervation as a non-autoimmune route to sicca distinguishable by a pilocarpine challenge, and `@lim:ocular-surface-mecfs-confounds` consolidating the critical case (medication-induced sicca, dry-eye confound, spurious tear-proteomic overlap, zero direct data); Chapter 3, `sec-10-ocular` vision Mechanism paragraph cross-referenced to the two sicca-mechanism speculations; hypothesis registry, 4 new entries; `bib/autoimmunity.bib`, 3 new entries and `bib/neurology-comorbidities.bib`, 3 new entries with `research_stream=ocular-sjogren-mecfs-overlap`; Appendix H, 6 new annotated entries]): A narrowly scoped follow-on to the post-COVID ocular cycle (Gate A scope-escalation), covering the *ocular-surface* dimension of the long-noted Sjögren's–ME/CFS overlap — distinct from the already-integrated M3-muscarinic-autoantibody and seronegative-Sjögren's material. Six papers (all certainty 0.50–0.55): Sjögren's tear proteomics discriminates autoimmune from non-autoimmune dry eye @lepine2024tearproteomics @george2023tearproteomics, tear IL-6/IL-17/MMP-9/BAFF track systemic activity @wu2024sjogrendryeyediagnostics, and corneal confocal microscopy detects small-fiber loss in Sjögren's @luzu2022cornealinnervation @wang2025ivcmsjogren and fibromyalgia dry eye @verges2025fibrodryeye. Because CCM already images corneal small fibers in ME/CFS and post-COVID cohorts, the corneal nerve plexus is a candidate common small-fiber observable; whether the ocular surface additionally *integrates* immune and nerve signals into a systemic window in ME/CFS is explicitly untested (no ME/CFS tear or primary-endpoint CCM study exists). A competing, non-autoimmune sicca mechanism (functional lacrimal parasympathetic denervation) is proposed alongside the existing M3-autoantibody account as a non-exclusive tension, with a pilocarpine challenge to distinguish them. The integration is deliberately balanced by an equal-visibility limitation surfacing the strongest objections — anticholinergic-medication-induced sicca (the simplest alternative), dry-eye-driven tear/corneal changes, spurious overlap as a shared dry-eye endotype, and the absolute absence of direct ME/CFS ocular data. Clinical relevance LOW–MEDIUM: no actionable ME/CFS ocular test today, but corneal confocal microscopy and tear collection are low-burden and feasible even for severe/bedbound patients if validated. Cholinergic-agonist content is flagged as a research hypothesis, not a recommendation, with contraindications stated. Quality flags: none (PROCEED; 0% of papers below certainty 0.40; net certainty change 0.00 — purely additive). _Motivated by:_ @wu2024sjogrendryeyediagnostics — establishes that tear IL-6/IL-17/MMP-9/BAFF track systemic Sjögren's activity, the biochemical bridge motivating the ocular-surface-window hypothesis; @luzu2022cornealinnervation and @wang2025ivcmsjogren — corneal confocal microscopy detects and grades small-fiber/serological pathology in Sjögren's, supplying the cross-disease precedent for a shared corneal-nerve observable; @verges2025fibrodryeye — first ocular-surface pathology documented in a fatigue-spectrum condition (fibromyalgia), the closest available analogue to ME/CFS.

- *Pupillometry as Autonomic Dysfunction Biomarker — Cross-Disease Validation, GPCR Autoantibody Bridge, Convergent Synthesis* ([Chapter 29, new `@sec:pupillometry-biomarker` with 3 speculations (`@spec:pupillometry-biomarker` cert 0.30, `@spec:pupillometry-lc-readout` cert 0.25), 5 open-questions (`@oq:pupillometry-pem`, `@oq:plr-gpcr-bioassay`, `@oq:plr-composite-score`, `@oq:plr-redundancy`, `@oq:plr-null-hypothesis`), 2 limitations, and `@syn:pupillometry-autonomic-biomarker-mecfs-model`; Chapter 8, `@spec:pupillometry-lc-readout` (cert 0.25) linking LC noradrenergic deficiency to noninvasive pupil-based LC assessment; Chapter 14d, `@spec:cross-disease-plr` (cert 0.35), `@oq:cross-disease-pupillometry`, and `@lim:no-modern-pupillometry-data`; hypothesis registry, 4 new entries; `bib/pupillometry.bib`, 14 new entries with `research_stream=pupillometry-autonomic-biomarker-mecfs` (key `smit2026pupillary` reused from postcovid-ocular-syndrome); Appendix H, 15 new annotated entries]): 14 papers found — zero modern ME/CFS pupillometry studies. Strong indirect evidence: M3 muscarinic and α1-adrenergic receptors controlling pupil constriction/dilation are the exact targets of autoantibodies elevated in ME/CFS (Szklarski 2021 @szklarski2021cd26, Azcue 2026 @azcue2026gpcrpupil) — though Germain 2025 (n=172, negative across all GPCRs @Germain2025autoantibody) and Vernino 2022 (100% CellTrend control positivity in POTS @POTS2022failed_replication) contest this serological evidence. Cross-disease validation exists in diabetic neuropathy, pure autonomic failure, MS, and concussion @sander2025pupillometry @master2020plr. The integration establishes that pupillometry is a mechanistically compelling, low-cost, severe-patient-accessible biomarker candidate with no ME/CFS data — the evidence gap is actionable, not theoretical. Key constraints: binding ≠ functional blockade, medication/diurnal confounds may overwhelm disease signal, ocular redundancy could mask systemic autonomic dysfunction. Clinical relevance: LOW — research-only until an ME/CFS validation study is performed. _Motivated by:_ Szklarski et al. (2021) @szklarski2021cd26 — M3/α1 autoantibody elevation in ME/CFS provided a direct biochemical bridge from established ME/CFS pathology to a specific, noninvasive, quantitative autonomic measurement that had never been performed in ME/CFS. De-Rosez Benavent et al. (2019) @derodezbenavent2019autonomic — demonstrated retinal/autonomic coupling in MS, establishing precedent for ocular-autonomic integration; Sander et al. (2025) @sander2025pupillometry — validated handheld pupillometry in autonomic failure, proving clinical feasibility.

- *Corneal Confocal Microscopy Cross-Disease SFN Validation — Normative Data, Specificity Caveats, and Convergent Model* ([Chapter 10, expanded `@spec:sfn-interface-failure` (cert 0.40→0.45) with cross-disease CCM evidence paragraph, new `@oq:ccm-trigeminal-vs-systemic`, `@spec:ccm-tortuosity-composite-score` (cert 0.30), `@lim:ccm-mecfs-evidence-quality`, and `@syn:ccm-cross-disease-sfn-model`; Chapter 14d, new `@spec:ccm-cross-disease-patterns` (cert 0.35) with seven-disease comparative table and `@oq:ccm-sjogren-overlap-pattern`; Chapter 8, new `@spec:corneal-lc-microglia-proxy` (cert 0.15); Chapter 41, new `@spec:tortuosity-ode-state-variable` (cert 0.20) extending SFN ODE with separate tortuosity dynamics; hypothesis registry, 3 new entries; `bib/neurology-comorbidities.bib`, 15 new entries with `research_stream=corneal-confocal-cross-disease-sfn`; Appendix H, 15 new annotated entries]): A cross-disease CCM literature sweep (15 papers across seven disease groups) found multinational normative data (Tavakoli 2015 @tavakoli2015normaliveccm, cert 0.80), ~59% SFN detection in fibromyalgia @sommer2025fibromyalgiasfn, and disease-specific CCM signatures in MS, Parkinson's, SLE, and POTS. Key constraint: CCM and skin biopsy (IENFD) show only moderate correlation @ghadban2025mixed — they are complementary, not interchangeable. The integration establishes that the single ME/CFS CCM study (Azcue 2025, AUC=0.720) is a principled measurement with cross-disease precedent, but the tortuosity-dominant, non-length-dependent pattern may reflect trigeminal-specific neuropathy rather than systemic SFN (Section oq:ccm-trigeminal-vs-systemic) — no concurrent IENFD measurement exists to distinguish. The paper's SFN ODE (@eq:sfn-dynamics) is extended with a two-variable model separating tortuosity (ECM degradation → fiber kinking) from density (axonal die-back). Clinical relevance: MEDIUM — CCM offers a validated, non-invasive, repeatable alternative to skin biopsy for SFN assessment, but ME/CFS-specific normative comparison and trigeminal-vs-systemic resolution are needed before clinical deployment. _Motivated by:_ Tavakoli et al. (2015) @tavakoli2015normaliveccm — a multinational CCM normative database existed but the paper's SFN discussion cited only Azcue 2025 without cross-disease context; the cross-disease evidence confirms CCM as a general neuropathy tool while identifying the specific validation gaps ME/CFS research must address.

- *Post-COVID Ocular Syndrome — Confirmatory Evidence for the Dysautonomia–Neuropathy–Immune Triad and Tear Proteomics as a Novel Biomarker Window* ([Chapter 8, new `@cf:postcovid-ocular-syndrome` (cert 0.75) and `@lim:postcovid-ocular-mecfs-gap`, plus cross-reference added to the existing `@spec:retinal-corneal-cns-window` (certainty held at 0.25 — corneal arm corroborated, retinal OCT-A arm still untested in ME/CFS); Chapter 7, new `@spec:tear-tcell-readout` (cert 0.35) linking the tear CD4+ T-cell dysregulation signature to the existing T-cell exhaustion framework `@hyp:tcell-exhaust-ev-downstream`; Chapter 3, `sec-10-ocular` vision section extended with adult-onset strabismus and pupillary photophobia mechanism plus new `@spec:fl41-photophobia` (cert 0.25); Chapter 41, SFN ODE (`@eq:sfn-dynamics`) extended with new `@pred:cnfd-sfn-observable` (cert 0.35) making corneal nerve fibre density a non-invasive observable for the abstract fibre-density state variable; hypothesis registry, 3 new entries; `bib/neurology-comorbidities.bib`, 4 new entries with `research_stream=postcovid-ocular-syndrome` (3 pre-existing keys reused: `Cañadas2023CornealConfocal`, `Azcue2025sfn`, `Azcue2023sfn`); Appendix H, 4 new annotated entries; three scope-escalation topics queued for future integration cycles: Sjögren's tear overlap, pupillometry autonomic biomarker, corneal-confocal cross-disease SFN]): Moustardas et al.\ (2026, Nature Communications, PMID 42420292; n=100 non-hospitalised post-mild-COVID patients with persistent ocular symptoms, n=32 mild-COVID controls) found that standard ophthalmic examination is normal while specialised testing reveals a convergent triad — corneal small-nerve degeneration with dendritic/T-cell activation (peripheral neuropathy), weakened autonomic pupillary reflexes and adult-onset strabismus (dysautonomia), and a tear-fluid CD4+ T-cell dysregulation proteomic signature matching severe/fatal COVID blood and tissue patterns (immune dysregulation). Two diagnostic models achieved 77% (instrument-only) to 91% (instrument + tear proteomics) accuracy. This is largely *confirmatory* of the paper's existing causal hierarchy (CNS energy crisis propagating through autonomic, small-fibre, and T-cell-mediated immune channels): the eye is a tissue where all three channels are simultaneously and non-invasively measurable. The genuinely new elements are tear-fluid proteomics (a biofluid the paper had not covered), a formal ocular diagnostic model, and adult-onset strabismus as a clinical sign. Integration decision: PROCEED (2 papers ≥0.60: Moustardas 0.75, Smit 2026 pupillometry 0.65; 0 null). Clinical relevance: MEDIUM — biomarker/diagnostic value (corneal confocal, tear proteomics, pupillometry as accessible windows), not a treatment. Key caveat: the Moustardas cohort was selected for ocular symptoms and never screened against ME/CFS criteria, so ME/CFS equivalence is held as a limitation, not asserted; tear proteomics has never been performed in an ME/CFS cohort; single study, unreplicated; no null studies were found (publication bias not excludable). _Motivated by:_ @moustardas2026ocular — direct multimodal evidence tying post-COVID ocular symptoms to the same dysautonomia+SFN+immune triad the paper models for ME/CFS; @smit2026pupillary — independent large-cohort (n=526) confirmation of pupillary autonomic dysregulation in post-COVID syndrome.

- *Peripheral Serotonin Depletion as Multi-System Convergence Mechanism* ([Chapter 13, new `@hyp:peripheral-serotonin-convergence` (cert 0.50), `@oq:serotonin-null-hypothesis`, `@syn:peripheral-serotonin-depletion-model`; Chapter 14d, `@spec:cross-disease-serotonin-convergence` (cert 0.50); Chapter 8, `@spec:bidirectional-serotonin` cert 0.25→0.20 and `@hyp:enterochromaffin-vagal` cert 0.40→0.45 with new evidence; Chapter 11, IDO2 section enhanced with wong2023serotonin, che2025innate, gunning2016pots, mar2014ssripots; dietary tryptophan confound caveats added to ch08 and ch11 tryptophan sections; Chapter 8, 95%→99% kynurenine diversion arithmetic flagged as illustrative; `bib/long-covid.bib` +6, `bib/autonomic-cardiovascular.bib` +3, `bib/pain-fibromyalgia.bib` +2, `bib/immune.bib` +3 (14 entries); Appendix H, 14 new annotated entries; hypothesis registry, 1 new entry]): Wong et al. (Cell, 2023, @wong2023serotonin) identified three converging peripheral serotonin depletion mechanisms in Long COVID; Gunning et al. (2016, n=181, @gunning2016pots) found 81% platelet serotonin deficiency in POTS with SSRI RCT harm signal (Mar et al. 2014, @mar2014ssripots). ME/CFS-specific evidence is limited: Che et al. 2025 (@che2025innate) shows innate immune-driven tryptophan diversion; Raij & Raij 2024 (@raij2024serotonin) found lower serotonin in n=38 CFS patients. Cross-disease convergence across ME/CFS, Long COVID, POTS, and fibromyalgia supports peripheral serotonin as a candidate common pathway linking gut dysbiosis, IDO-mediated tryptophan diversion, enterochromaffin cell damage, and platelet storage defects to mitochondrial dysfunction, vagal impairment, orthostatic intolerance, and pain amplification. Clinical relevance: MEDIUM — SSRI caution in ME/CFS with confirmed POTS comorbidity is the only actionable signal. Key caveats: dietary tryptophan intake never controlled; strongest evidence from Long COVID/POTS, not ME/CFS; zero ME/CFS interventional data for serotonin restoration; single n=38 ME/CFS serotonin study unreplicated. The integration consolidates the hypothesis into a single primary location (ch13) to avoid density illusion from citation repetition across 4+ chapters. _Motivated by:_ @wong2023serotonin — three converging serotonin depletion mechanisms in Cell; @che2025innate — innate immune tryptophan diversion confirmation in ME/CFS; @gunning2016pots — 81% POTS platelet serotonin deficiency (n=181).

- *EBV Serology Interpretation — High VCA IgG with Low Active-Reactivation Markers Is Serologically Ambiguous* ([Chapter 29, `@subsec:viral-reactivation-biomarkers` extended with an interpretive paragraph explaining that very high VCA IgG (\>750) plus negative/low EA-D and negative PCR cannot be resolved by serology alone — it is equally consistent with an inert post-infectious antibody set-point, with ongoing abortive lytic replication (an active, potentially antiviral-responsive process; @sec:abortive-lytic), or with episodic/tissue-compartmentalised reactivation; the paragraph also notes the poor negative predictive value of EA-D, the single-sample limitation of plasma PCR, and the platform-dependence of the \>750 threshold; Chapter 24, antiviral patient-selection limitations augmented with a matching caveat that high VCA IgG neither confirms nor excludes active reactivation, that the only controlled positive trials (Lerner 2007, Montoya 2013) enrolled on elevated titres rather than confirmed replication, that confirmatory markers support rather than gate the treatment decision, and that a time-limited valacyclovir trial with a predefined stopping rule remains reasonable when confirmatory tests are negative or unavailable; `<sec:antivirals>` label bound to its heading in both directory and monolith ch24 sources to make it referenceable]): Audit-driven clarification connecting three pieces the paper already contained but had not linked — the VCA IgG \>750 antiviral-selection threshold (ch24), the high-VCA serological note (ch29), and the abortive lytic replication framework resolving the "high serology, negative viral load" paradox (ch07 @sec:abortive-lytic). The clarification deliberately avoids a serology-only verdict: an earlier draft framed the pattern as a "post-infectious footprint," but adversarial review showed that reading contradicts the abortive-lytic model (which predicts the identical assay-negative pattern from an active process) and is more restrictive than the enrollment criteria of the only positive trials. The corrected text presents all three states as serologically inseparable and reframes confirmatory testing as supporting, not gating, the clinical decision. _Motivated by:_ user audit request confirming the topic is already thoroughly developed — the genuine gap was the missing interpretive link to @sec:abortive-lytic, and the genuine risk was over-reading an ambiguous serological pattern in either direction.

- *Antigen-Specific IgE Sensitization to Spike/Tick Antigens — PARTIAL Integration with Replicated-Null Constraint* ([Chapter 14b, new section `@sec:ige-antigen-sensitization` with `@lim:ige-normal-mecfs`, `@spec:ige-antigen-subset` (cert 0.20), `@spec:infection-allergic-sensitization` (cert 0.30), `@oq:ige-vs-nonige-neuroinflammation`, `@lim:nonige-mcas-parsimony` (cert 0.60), `@lim:antispike-ige-transient` (cert 0.45), `@lim:alphagal-phenotype-mismatch` (cert 0.50), `@oq:antispike-ige-serosurvey`, `@lim:ige-measurement-caveats` (cert 0.55), and convergent `@syn:ige-sensitization-spike-tick-neuroinflammation-model`; Chapter 7, `@sec:allergic-responses` corrected — "elevated IgE in subsets" replaced with the replicated-null finding, Th2-bias citation added, cross-reference to the new section; hypothesis registry, 3 new entries (2 speculations + 1 open-question, plus the serosurvey open-question); `bib/immune.bib`, 18 new entries with `research_stream=ige-sensitization-spike-tick-neuroinflammation`; Appendix H, 18 new annotated entries]): A widely-circulated patient-community hypothesis holds that some people are "allergic" (mount an IgE response) to SARS-CoV-2 spike or tick-borne pathogen antigens, with mast-cell neuroinflammation producing cognitive and neuropsychiatric symptoms. A systematic search (18 papers) found the core claim *unstudied in ME/CFS*: anti-spike or anti-tick IgE has never been measured in ME/CFS patients, and two independent studies report total IgE (Repka-Ramirez 2001) and allergen-specific IgE (Kowal 2002) to be *normal* in ME/CFS — a replicated null. Integration decision: PARTIAL — the topic is integrated only as speculation, open-questions, and limitations, with the non-IgE mast-cell-activation paradigm presented as the better-supported model and the replicated null given equal visibility. Supporting evidence is real but indirect: spike-specific IgE exists in acute COVID, tick bites generate antigen-specific IgE (alpha-gal), and infection raises incident allergic disease at population scale (Oh 2024, n=836k). The hypothesis is cheaply falsifiable via a three-group anti-spike IgE serosurvey. Clinical relevance: LOW (research-only). Quality note: WEAK-EVIDENCE — evidence base is preliminary and indirect; no clinical action is implied. _Motivated by:_ Repka-Ramirez 2001 @reparramirez2001igelevels and Kowal 2002 @kowal2002prevalence — the replicated null on IgE in ME/CFS that constrains the entire hypothesis; Oh 2024 @oh2024incident — population-scale evidence that infection can trigger allergic disease, the strongest indirect support.

- *Extracellular Vesicle Count Elevation in ME/CFS — Rydland 2026 Replication and Dual-Pathway Mechanistic Model* ([Chapter 7, updated `@spec:ev-signaling-mecfs` (cert 0.25→0.45) with Rydland 2026 and 5 prior EV studies establishing EV count elevation as a consistently replicated finding, new `@spec:ev-dual-pathway-count` (cert 0.20) proposing ceramide-driven + complement-driven + clearance-impaired model, updated `@spec:exosome-biogenesis-impairment` (cert 0.25→0.20) reconciling ESCRT impairment with elevated total EV counts; Chapter 7, new `@lim:ev-evidence-quality-caveats` and `@oq:ev-proteomics-power-study` and `@oq:ev-longitudinal-studies`; hypothesis registry, 3 new/updated entries; `bib/immune.bib`, 10 new entries with `research_stream=extracellular-vesicles-rydland-2026`; `bib/sleep.bib`, 1 pre-existing entry fixed (missing closing brace); Appendix H, 11 new annotated entries; pre-existing build fixes in ch32 (`@spec:fi-severity-spiral` bold+ref parsing) and hypothesis registry (2 unresolved label references)]): Rydland et al. (2026, n=49 ME/CFS Canadian criteria, n=50 HC — largest EV study to date) confirmed elevated circulating EV counts in ME/CFS, replicating 5+ prior studies from 4 independent groups. Eleven nominally-significant EV proteins identified (liver-derived upregulated: ITIH3, AMBP, FGB; B-cell/erythrocyte-derived downregulated: immunoglobulin light chains, hemoglobin, F13A1) but none survived FDR correction — the data are compatible with chance (11 hits vs 21.2 expected). The integration proposes a dual-pathway model: ceramide/nSMase2-driven ESCRT-independent exosome production + complement C5b-9-mediated microvesicle shedding + impaired clearance, mechanistically linked to existing ceramide:S1P and complement hypotheses. Quality: WEAK-EVIDENCE (PARTIAL; zero FDR-significant proteins); clinical relevance LOW. _Motivated by:_ Rydland 2026 @rydland2026evcargo — largest EV proteomics study in ME/CFS, replicating EV count elevation, with novel protein cargo findings requiring critical-evidence framing.

- *Food Insecurity in ME/CFS and Long COVID — Socioeconomic Disease Burden Integration* ([Chapter 32, new `@ach:food-insecurity-disease-burden`, `@spec:hiv-food-assistance-template` (cert 0.50), `@spec:fi-severity-spiral` (cert 0.40), `@spec:fi-null-hypothesis` (cert 0.25), `@oq:fi-screening-protocol`, `@lim:fi-causality-undetermined`, `@lim:fi-evidence-quality`, `@syn:food-insecurity-model`; Chapter 1, demographics updated with food insecurity mention; Chapter 21, very-severe pathway updated with screening recommendation; Chapter 32, demographic risk factors updated; Appendix H, new annotated entries for Dey 2026, Lin 2025, Datta 2025, Feldman 2025, Bowden 2026, Weigel 2025, Vester 2026, Samms 2025, Aguilar-Aguilar 2020, Jones 2017, Dorczok 2025 (11 entries); `bib/epidemiology.bib`, 15 new entries (11 core + 4 cross-disease/tool) with `research_stream=food-insecurity-me-cfs`; hypothesis registry, 6 new entries (1 achievement, 4 speculations, 1 open-question)]): Dey et al. (2026) first ME/CFS-specific food insecurity survey, New Zealand (n unreported). Cross-sectional evidence: Long COVID associated with elevated food insecurity (Lin 2025 n=21,631, aOR 1.73; Datta 2025 n=271,076); ME/CFS-specific evidence limited to single survey (Dey 2026). Achievement cert 0.55 (downgraded from 0.75 in review to reflect GRADE very-low rating and single-anchor ME/CFS evidence; see @lim:fi-evidence-quality). HIV template cert 0.50 (downgraded from 0.65 — structural analogy constrained by biological disanalogy: ME/CFS lacks HIV's disease-activity biomarkers). Cross-national evidence (Lin 2025 n=21,631; Datta 2025 n=271,076) confirms Long COVID independently increases food insecurity across income strata, with employment loss mediating 6–20% of the effect. Bowden 2026 (n=1,902) documents 18.3% ME/CFS employment vs 83.8% general population — the primary mechanism. The HIV food assistance template provides a 15-year clinical precedent for integrating food access into ME/CFS care. Integration decision: PROCEED (8 papers ≥0.40, 6 papers ≥0.70). Clinical relevance: MEDIUM — socioeconomic finding supporting clinical screening and disability benefit reform; no direct treatment implications. _Motivated by:_ Dey 2026 @dey2026foodinsecurity — first direct ME/CFS food insecurity assessment; Lin 2025 @lin2025longcovidfoodinsecurity — largest FI-LC association study (aOR 1.73, n=21,631).

- *tVNS for Post-COVID-19 Condition — Systematic Review and Null Controlled Trial Evidence Integration* ([Chapter 27, new `@spec:tvns-pcc-systematic-review` (cert 0.25) and `@spec:tvns-dissociation-mechanisms` (cert 0.20--0.55) and `@syn:tvns-pcc-model`; Chapter 26, new `@lim:tvns-pcc-null-evidence` (cert 0.65) and `@spec:tvns-evidence-quality-concerns` (cert 0.30--0.50); Chapter 14d, new `@oq:tvns-sham-superior-paradox`; Chapter 18, treatment table evidence qualifiers and research direction updated; Chapter 26, existing taVNS sections retroactively caveated with PCC null evidence; Chapter 27, existing tVNS mast cell-ECM speculation evidence base caveated; hypothesis registry, 6 new/updated entries (1 certainty reduction: VNS corticosteroid alternative 0.50→0.35); `bib/treatments.bib`, 9 new entries with `research_stream=tvns-pcc`; Appendix H, 9 new annotated entries]): Balan et al. (2026) systematic review of taVNS for post-COVID-19 condition — 5 studies (n=154), three RCTs, two single-arm — rated all efficacy outcomes as "very low" certainty (GRADE). Key finding: every adequately controlled trial found no superiority over sham, and the best-powered RCT (Percin et al., n~50) produced a paradoxical sham > active result for fatigue despite confirmed HRV engagement. This evidence constrains the paper's therapeutic inference from shared vagal dysfunction across PCC, ME/CFS, and POTS: the mechanistic framework (CAP, vagal-SPM coupling) remains biologically sound, but clinical evidence in the most analogous population is null. After adversarial review: the five-candidate mechanism framework was expanded (Candidate 0 — tVNS has no specific effect, cert 0.55; Candidate 2 — CAP engagement by auricular tVNS is unvalidated, cert 0.45). The synthesis acknowledges Teixeira 2024 positive sham-controlled tVNS RCT in POTS (n=26) as a counter-example. The tVNS mast cell-ECM clinical protocol carries a research-stage-only warning with severe-ME/CFS contraindication. All new tVNS-PCC content uses `#speculation`, `#open-question`, or `#limitation` environments. Quality note: WEAK-EVIDENCE (Phase 2 PARTIAL; >50% papers weak). Clinical relevance: LOW. Pre-existing optimistic tVNS claims retroactively caveated (6 contradiction adaptations, 3 reinforcement citations, 1 certainty reduction 0.50→0.35). Net certainty: −0.15. _Motivated by:_ Balan et al.\ 2026 @Balan2026taVNS — systematic review with GRADE framework; Percin et al.\ 2025 @Percin2025taVNS — best-powered double-blind RCT showing sham superiority.

- *Consolidated Research Proposals Index* ([Part 4, new `@ch:research-proposals-index` — 50 proposals sorted by impact × feasibility / cost in a single table; main entry point updated to include after ch36]): Aggregated every research proposal scattered across 8 chapters (Chapters 29, 34, 35, 36, 14d, and Phase 3 integrations) into a single sortable decision tool. Proposals span 6 types: observational (12), interventional (10), biomarker-development (15), infrastructure (6), secondary-analysis (6), preclinical (4). Sorted into 5 tiers by impact-weighted feasibility — Tier 1 identifies 7 experiments achievable with existing data at low cost. Every row cross-references the full protocol or source environment. _Motivated by:_ user request — the paper lacked a single consolidated view of its research proposals, making it impractical for funders and investigators to identify highest-leverage experiments.

- *Direct Tissue Examination Findings — Into the Tissues We Go* ([Chapter 8, new `@spec:retinal-corneal-cns-window` (cert 0.25) and `@oq:retinal-ab-protective-vs-pathological` — retinal/corneal imaging as non-invasive CNS window; Chapter 14b, new `@spec:ln-fna-gc-dysfunction` (cert 0.20), `@oq:ebv-ln-gc-dysfunction`, and `@spec:gc-niche-antibody-seeding` (cert 0.15) — lymph node FNA germinal center analysis as immunological frontier; Chapter 14d, new `@spec:tissue-pathology-rule` (cert 0.30), `@oq:tissue-blood-undersampling`, `@spec:arterial-plaque-efferocytosis` (cert 0.25), `@spec:larazotide-mecfs-gap` (cert 0.15), `@spec:blood-biomarker-limitation` (cert 0.20), `@lim:tissue-findings-evidence-quality`, `@oq:tissue-findings-null-hypothesis`; Chapter 7, compartmentalized immunity enhanced with @Eberhardt2023CoronaryPlaque citation; hypothesis registry, 6 new entries; long-covid.bib and brain-clearance.bib, 14 new entries with `research_stream=tissue-level-findings`; Appendix H, 13 new annotated entries]): Integration of 6 symposium presentations covering direct tissue examination across six compartments [...]

- *Sleep Synaptic Reset — SV2A PET Evidence for Synaptic Homeostasis in Healthy Adults, Speculatively Applied to ME/CFS Unrefreshing Sleep* ([Chapter 8, new `@spec:ch08-synaptic-downscaling-failure` (cert 0.30) — alpha-delta sleep may impair NREM synaptic downscaling (six-link inferential chain, zero links tested under ME/CFS-relevant conditions), and `@oq:ch08-sv2a-pet-me-cfs` — SV2A PET as test of synaptic homeostasis failure in ME/CFS, `@oq:ch08-csf-synaptic-panel` — CSF synaptic protein panel as lower-cost alternative, `@oq:ch08-optogenetic-alpha-sleep` — optogenetic causal test of alpha intrusion on synaptic downscaling; Appendix H, new `@sec:bib-sleep-synaptic-reset` section with 14 annotated entries; bib/sleep.bib, 14 new entries with `research_stream=sleep-synaptic-reset`; hypothesis registry, 2 new entries (1 speculation, 1 open-question)]): Elmenhorst et al. (2026, PLOS Biology, n=40 healthy adults) provided first direct in vivo human evidence for the synaptic homeostasis hypothesis (SHY) — one night sleep deprivation increased SV2A PET binding (synaptic density proxy) in thalamus (+4.6%), hippocampus (+5.6%), parietal cortex (+3.2%), while normal sleep controls showed no change. SV2A increase correlated with elevated slow-wave activity during recovery sleep. ME/CFS alpha-delta sleep — alpha (8–12 Hz, wake-like) EEG intrusion into NREM delta sleep (0.5–4 Hz) — may prevent the nightly synaptic downscaling that normal deep sleep provides, but this causal link is untested (0.30 certainty). Key caveats: zero ME/CFS-specific SV2A data exist; Elmenhorst 2026 is a single study, not yet replicated; SV2A PET signal may reflect vesicle cycling state rather than synapse count (Mikkelsen 2023 @Mikkelsen2023SV2Apostmortem); SHY generality challenged in visual cortex (Durkin & Aton 2016 @Durkin2016SHYcounter); adenosine accumulation provides a competing neurochemical mechanism that does not require synaptic structural change. Quality note: WEAK-EVIDENCE — all evidence from healthy general-population subjects; integration as speculation/open-question only. Clinical relevance: LOW — research-only; no clinical action follows until SV2A measured in ME/CFS cohorts. _Motivated by:_ Elmenhorst et al. 2026 @Elmenhorst2026SV2Asleep — first in vivo human evidence that sleep deprivation prevents synaptic reset; Tononi & Cirelli 2003–2019 SHY framework @Tononi2003SHY @Tononi2014SHYneuron; de Vivo 2017 ultrastructural EM evidence @DeVivo2017SHYultrastructural; Diering 2017 Homer1a molecular mechanism @Diering2017Homer1aSHY. @VanElzakker2024NeuroinflammationPASC), and retinal microcirculation–fatigue correlation (Schlick 2022 @Schlick2022RetinalMicrocirc). The central methodological thesis — that blood-based biomarkers systematically underestimate tissue-level pathology — is supported by the collective weight of disparate single-compartment studies but has never been tested in a multi-compartment study in the same patients. Quality note: WEAK-EVIDENCE — Phase 2 decision was PARTIAL; 0 of 15 papers involve ME/CFS patients directly; all integration uses speculation and open-question environments only. Integration decision: PARTIAL (evidence passes REJECT threshold but lacks ME/CFS-specific confirmation for PROCEED). Clinical relevance: LOW (research-only). _Motivated by:_ @Eberhardt2023CoronaryPlaque — demonstration of SARS-CoV-2 spike protein persistence in coronary plaque macrophages two years post-infection, establishing arterial tissue as a reservoir invisible to blood; @Lederer2022LymphNodeGC — validation of ultrasound-guided LN FNA method for germinal center analysis applicable to post-infectious syndromes; @Miller2025RetinalAmyloid — SARS-CoV-2-induced retinal Aβ pathology establishing retina as a CNS tissue window.

- *Intrapulmonary Right-Left Shunt as Post-Viral Tissue Hypoxia Mechanism* ([Chapter 6, new `@oq:intrapulmonary-shunt-mecfs`, `@spec:rbc-ipava-synergy` (cert 0.20), `@spec:post-exertional-shunt-window` (cert 0.20), `@syn:intrapulmonary-shunt-model`; Chapter 14d, new `@spec:intrapulmonary-shunt-postviral` (cert 0.35), `@spec:shunt-hif-imbalance` (cert 0.25); Chapter 28, citation insertion in altitude-medicine comparison; hypothesis registry, 5 new entries; vascular.bib, 11 new entries; Appendix H, 11 new annotated entries]): Full pipeline integration establishing intrapulmonary right-left shunt (Qs/Qt elevated to ~8% at 6 months post-COVID despite normal PFTs, normal DLCO, normal VO₂max) as a candidate proximal mechanism for tissue hypoxia in post-viral ME/CFS. Key finding: zero direct ME/CFS shunt measurements exist — all evidence from Long COVID (Farrow 2023 @Farrow2023IntrapulmonaryShunt, cert 0.62; Harbut 2023 @Harbut2023IntrapulmonaryShunt, cert 0.62) and general exercise physiology (Durand 2020 @Durand2020EIHemodynamic, cert 0.60). Anatomical substrate documented: IPAVAs present in ~30% of adults, HPV impaired post-COVID @Li2024RepercussionsShunt. The "normal PFTs with desaturation" paradox is mechanistically explained by shunt — adding a *reduced arterial O₂ content* source upstream of the microcirculatory and mitochondrial bottlenecks already described in Chapter 6. Compatibility audit: 3 feed-in relationships (shunt → HIF pathway inertia, PEM hibernation-mimetic, β2AR-negative HIF-2α subtype) and 1 reinforcement (shunt → tissue hypoxia model). Quality note: WEAK-EVIDENCE — no ME/CFS-specific data; all evidence from Long COVID cohorts or general physiology. Integration decision: PARTIAL (evidence passes numerical PROCEED thresholds but zero direct ME/CFS confirmation). Clinical relevance: MEDIUM — if confirmed, opens therapeutic axis of O₂ supplementation during exertion for shunt-positive subset. _Motivated by:_ @Farrow2023IntrapulmonaryShunt — first demonstration of persistent intrapulmonary shunt (Qs/Qt ~8%) at 6 months post-COVID with normal PFTs, independent replication by @Sandhu2026AlveolarDeadspace.

- *ADHD-ASD Comorbidity Genetics — Formal Citation Support for Existing Cross-Disease Framework* ([Chapter 14d, enhanced Architecture A/B/C sections with ADHD-ASD comorbidity-specific citations from 12 new papers (twin studies, GWAS, cross-disorder analyses, clinical reviews); `epidemiology.bib`, 13 new entries with `research_stream=adhd-asd-comorbidity-mecfs`; Appendix H, 12 new annotated bibliography entries]): Light integration — no new environments, no brainstorm. Enhanced 8 existing ch14d passages with formal genetic correlation data ($r_"g" = 0.32$--$0.60$ across methods), ADHD-in-ASD prevalence (28%, Lai 2019), familial co-aggregation (OR=22.33, Ghirardi 2018), trait-level correlations ($r=0.51$, Polderman 2014), and ADHD+ASD compound row in the metabolic reserve reducer table. The ADHD-ASD shared genetic architecture provides the biological plausibility foundation for the paper's existing Architecture C compound-risk argument. Key new insight: ADHD+ASD = twice-hit BH4 bottleneck — consumption from dopaminergic demand + oxidative destruction from IL-6. _Motivated by:_ prior completion of ADHD and ASD standalone integrations; ADHD-ASD relationship already treated organically but lacked formal comorbidity literature citations.

- *Brain Energy Metabolism: ASD-ME/CFS Cross-Disease Convergent Framework* ([Chapter 6, new `@spec:astrocyte-brain-energy-conservation` (cert 0.40) — astrocyte-mediated brain energy conservation as cognitive dysfunction mechanism converging with ASD brain energy disorder model; `@oq:brain-hypometabolism-primary-vs-secondary` — four models for primary vs secondary brain hypometabolism; `@oq:ketogenic-diet-brain-energy` — ketogenic diet for brain energy restoration; `@lim` — brain hypometabolism as epiphenomenon; `@lim` — no direct astrocytic evidence; `@oq:brain-metabolism-specificity-fatigue` — null hypothesis of non-specificity; `@spec:ketone-esters-mct-bypass` (cert 0.30) — ketone esters + MCT oil for brain glucose bypass; `@oq:csf-plasma-glucose-ratio` — CSF:plasma glucose as GLUT1 bottleneck biomarker; `@oq:glut1-deficiency-mecfs-model` — G1D as monogenic ME/CFS model; `@spec:severity-adapted-brain-energy` (cert 0.20) — severity-adapted brain energy protocol; Chapter 8, PET metabolic findings enhanced with ASD-ME/CFS cross-disease convergence paragraph; Chapter 13, unified model expanded with brain energy metabolism bullet; Appendix H, 4 new annotated bibliography entries from ASD source paper; energy-metabolism.bib, 16 new entries with `research_stream=brain-energy-asd-mecfs`; hypothesis registry, 6 new entries (1 speculation, 4 open-questions, 1 limitation)]): Blagojevic-Stokic et al. (2026) proposed autism spectrum disorder as a brain energy disorder — astrocytic glucose metabolism dysfunction → ATP shortage → "energy-saving adaptation" sacrificing higher cognitive functions to preserve ATP for survival. ME/CFS independently exhibits all core biochemical features of this model: FDG-PET regional brain glucose hypometabolism, elevated ventricular lactate on MRS, astrocyte dysfunction in central fatigue pathways, and an independently proposed energy conservation model (Lacourt 2018) structurally identical to the ASD model despite no cross-reference. Key insight: the ASD model's "energy-saving barter" — sacrificing cognitive flexibility, novel processing, and social engagement under energy constraint — maps precisely onto ME/CFS cognitive symptoms (brain fog, impaired task-switching, sensory overload). Cross-disease convergence is striking: two different conditions studied by different research communities converge on the same mechanistic framework. Clinical relevance: LOW — research-stage mechanistic framework. Integration decision: PROCEED (4 papers ≥ 0.60 certainty, 6 ≥ 0.50). No clinical recommendations — all interventions (ketone esters, MCT oil, severity-adapted protocols) are research-stage with zero ME/CFS trial data. Quality note: no direct astrocytic evidence in ME/CFS — all evidence is indirect (FDG-PET bulk-metabolism, MRS bulk-metabolite, pathway-level inference). CSF:plasma glucose ratio and astrocyte-derived EV GLUT1 are minimal required evidence steps before clinical translation. _Motivated by:_ Blagojevic-Stokic et al. 2026 @BlagojevicStokic2026brainenergy — comprehensive ASD brain energy disorder review providing mechanistic framework for cross-disease convergence; Lacourt et al. 2018 @Lacourt2018InflammationEnergy — independently proposed identical energy conservation model for ME/CFS fatigue.

- *Emotional Processing, Interoceptive Processing, and Illness Cognitions in ME/CFS — Biological Foundations of Emotional Symptoms* ([Chapter 15, new `acolades` `@ach:ch15-inflammation-interoception-hub` (cert 0.70) — inflammation directly modulates interoceptive hub regions, `@sec:ch15-inflammation-interoception` — inflammation-to-interoception pathway, `@sec:ch15-interoceptive-dissociation` — interoceptive accuracy-sensibility dissociation with `@hyp:ch15-interoceptive-dissociation` (cert 0.45) and `@spec:ch15-greenhouse-tucknott-fatigue` (cert 0.40), `@sec:ch15-emotional-interoceptive` — emotional-interoceptive dysfunction as downstream biology with `@hyp:ch15-sickness-emotional-phenotype` (cert 0.45), `@hyp:ch15-alexithymia-acquired` (cert 0.45), and `@spec:ch15-emotional-autonomic-dissociation` (cert 0.40); Chapter 15, new `@oq:tripartite-interoception-mecfs`, `@oq:post-infectious-interoceptive-trajectory`, `@oq:interoceptive-training-mecfs`, and `@spec:ch15-afferent-noise-precision-hysteresis` (cert 0.40) in research directions; Chapter 33, catastrophizing critique extended with Poort 2021 null mediation evidence @Poort2021catastrophizingNull and Sohl/Friedberg 2008 recall bias finding @SohlFriedberg2008catastrophizingRecall; Chapter 15, graded exposure section strengthened with Poort 2021 null mediation context; Appendix H, new section `sec:bib-emotional-interoceptive-processing` with 20 annotated bibliography entries; pathophysiology-general.bib, 21 new entries with `research_stream=emotional-interoceptive-processing`; hypothesis registry, 7 new entries (1 achievement, 4 hypotheses, 2 speculations)]): Comprehensive integration establishing that altered emotional recognition, alexithymia, interoceptive accuracy-sensibility dissociation, fatigue catastrophizing, and sickness behavior reflect downstream consequences of neuroimmune and autonomic dysfunction rather than upstream psychological causes. Core framework: the Garfinkel et al.\ 2015 tripartite interoception model (accuracy/sensibility/awareness) @Garfinkel2015interoceptionAccuracy predicts a dissociation in ME/CFS — elevated interoceptive sensibility (hypervigilance) with reduced interoceptive accuracy (due to cytokine-corrupted afferent signals via vagal paraganglia @Harrison2009inflammationInteroception @SavitzHarrison2018interoception). Barrett's Constructed Emotion Theory @Barrett2025ConstructedEmotion provides the computational framework: degraded interoceptive input → impaired emotion category construction → acquired alexithymia. Greenhouse-Tucknott et al.\ 2022 @GreenhouseTucknott2022predictiveCodingFatigue and Manjaly/Critchley 2019 @ManjalyCritchley2019MSfatigue provide cross-disease predictive coding models of fatigue perception. Zhang, Wager et al.\ 2025 7T fMRI @ZhangWager2025AllostaticInteroceptive maps the allostatic-interoceptive system at high resolution. Key tension resolved: emotional/interoceptive symptoms are biologically real (not psychological) and track peripheral immune-autonomic dysfunction — consistent with NICE NG206 retiring CBT/GET and fear-avoidance as ME/CFS treatment rationale. Clinical relevance: MEDIUM — mechanistic context for treatment decisions; directs toward anti-inflammatory/autonomic targets for emotional symptoms. Quality note: No direct tripartite interoception study (Garfinkel protocol) has been conducted in ME/CFS — this is the single most impactful identified research gap. _Motivated by:_ @Garfinkel2015interoceptionAccuracy — established the tripartite framework essential for interpreting the accuracy-sensibility dissociation in ME/CFS; @Harrison2009inflammationInteroception — provided experimental evidence that inflammation directly modulates interoceptive brain regions.

- *Psychologization Critique — Schomerus et al.\ 2026 Five-Harm Framework* ([Chapter 33, new `@ach:psychologization-five-harms` (cert 0.70) — five psychologization harms taxonomy; new `@spec:harm-monitoring-gap` (cert 0.60) — regulatory asymmetry in harm monitoring for ME/CFS psychosocial trials; new `@spec:psychologization-lag-biomarker` (cert 0.40) — historical pattern of de-psychologization with biomarker discovery; new `@lim:psychologization-cross-sectional` — cross-sectional evidence base limitation with evidence-standards symmetry qualification; new `@oq:psychologization-prospective-cohort` — defining prospective study needed; clinical implications section; BPS asymmetry critique; Appendix H, new `+sec:bib-psychologization` section with 11 annotated bibliography entries; stigma.bib, 11 new entries with `research_stream=stigmatisation-psychologization`; hypothesis registry, 5 new entries (1 achievement, 2 speculations, 1 limitation, 1 open-question); PDF archive at `Literature/sociology/psychologization-critique-Schomerus-2026/`]): Integration of Schomerus et al.\ (2026) critical essay from \'7bPsychiatrische Praxis\'7d arguing against primary and secondary psychologization of ME/CFS and Long COVID, co-authored with people with lived experience. The essay articulates five specific harms from psychologization: iatrogenic deterioration from activation therapy, invalidation of illness experience undermining pacing, neglect of biomedical diagnosis/treatment, medico-legal disadvantage, and family/social harm. Supporting evidence from 11 papers including B\'fchner 2025 (46.8% of LC patients told symptoms psychological; n=1,156), Pantelic 2022 (37% above clinical stigma threshold), Cooper 2025 (GET 3-5\'d7 higher harm rate than pacing), and Hammer 2025 (72% reported damaging activating therapies). Adversarial review identified the cross-sectional nature of the evidence base as the primary vulnerability; the limitation and open-question explicitly address the untested alternative hypothesis that psychologization is epiphenomenal to disease severity. Clinical relevance: HIGH. _Motivated by:_ Schomerus et al.\ 2026 @Schomerus2026PsycheRole — a critical essay from within academic psychiatry providing the first systematic taxonomy of psychologization harms and arguing for evidence-based restraint in psychiatric attribution of post-infectious physical illness. ([Appendix D, new entry in `sec:disability-resources` under Key Considerations]): Added the Hidden Disabilities Sunflower lanyard as a practical accessibility tool for ME/CFS patients. The Sunflower is a discreet, internationally recognised signal (adopted by airports, train stations, supermarkets, hospitals, and other venues in 30+ countries) that the wearer has a non-visible disability and may need additional support, time, or understanding. No biomedical literature base or Phase 1–5 pipeline — this is a practical resource, not a mechanistic claim. Clinical relevance: HIGH — directly actionable for patients navigating public spaces. _Motivated by:_ a tool for addressing the "invisible illness" phenomenon discussed throughout the paper (Chapter 5, `sec:invisible-illness`).

- *Elevated Rheumatoid Factor in ME/CFS — Literature Review and DEFER Decision* ([Appendix H, new `== Elevated Rheumatoid Factor in ME/CFS` section with 5 annotated entries; autoimmunity.bib, 5 new entries with `research_stream=rf-elevated-mecfs`]): Systematic literature search found 13 papers — only 1 directly measures RF in a CFS cohort (Hashimoto 1992, n=51, 11.8% RF+, certainty 0.25, unreplicated in 34 years). The largest ME/CFS autoantibody profiling study (Germain 2025, n=172, certainty 0.65) found no autoantibody reactivity but did not specifically profile RF. A systematic review (Batham 2024, certainty 0.55) concluded insufficient evidence to classify ME/CFS as autoimmune. Integration decision: DEFER — the literature is too sparse and too weak (0 papers with certainty ≥ 0.50 directly measuring RF in a modern ME/CFS cohort) to support any mechanistic or clinical claim. No chapter modifications. Clinical relevance: LOW. Quality note: DEFER — evidence base insufficient. _Motivated by:_ Hashimoto 1992 @Hashimoto1992CFSRF — the only direct RF measurement in CFS, unreplicated; Germain 2025 @Germain2025autoantibody — the largest autoantibody null result in ME/CFS providing null context.

- *Mast Cell IgE Pathway → Connective Tissue Degradation in hEDS/POTS* ([Chapter 7, new `@spec:histaminylation-collagen` (cert 0.30) — mast cell histaminylation as MMP-independent collagen weakening via transglutaminase 2, and `@oq:ige-pathway-ct-mcas` — IgE-specific pathway in MCAS-connective tissue interaction; Chapter 14d, new `@spec:acquired-progressive-hypermobility-mc` (cert 0.35) — acquired progressive hypermobility via MC mediator-mediated CT degradation, `clin:progressive-hypermobility-algorithm` — clinical algorithm for evaluating progressive hypermobility, `@lim:hat-no-heds` — HaT null finding contextualisation, `@spec:cardiac-ecm-mc-prototype` (cert 0.60) — cardiac ECM as MC→CT degradation prototype, `@spec:periodontitis-ige-ct-model` (cert 0.55) — periodontitis as human IgE→MC→CT model, `@oq:omalizumab-ct-therapeutic-probe` — omalizumab as therapeutic probe, plus 3 limitations on non-MC CT degradation, non-IgE MC pathways, and evidence quality; Appendix H, 13 new annotated bibliography entries in mast cell section; mast-cell.bib, 13 new entries with `research_stream=mast-cell-ige-connective-tissue`; hypothesis registry, 6 new entries (3 Phase 3, 3 Phase 5); hypothesis tree subtree `mast-cell-ige-connective-tissue` with 46 nodes (6 integrated, 40 tree-only for future cycles)]): Mast cell proteases (tryptase→MMP-3/-13 @Magarinos2013TryptaseMMP, chymase→MMP-1 @Saarinen1994ChymaseMMP1) and histaminylation @Zhu2026HistaminylationCollagen provide two independent mechanisms for IgE-mediated connective tissue degradation. The cardiac ECM model @Janicki2006CardiacMastMMP and periodontitis model establish in vivo precedent for the IgE→MC→MMP→CT chain. Wilson 2026 (n=2141 hEDS/HSD) shows elevated IgE in the high-MC-score subset @Wilson2026MastCellScorehEDS; omalizumab is safe for MCAS @Matheny2025OmalizumabMCAS but never studied for CT outcomes. Clinical relevance: MEDIUM — provides mechanistic rationale for mast cell evaluation in progressive hypermobility and positions omalizumab as a therapeutic probe, but no validated treatment protocol exists. Key constraints: HaT does not cause hypermobility @Vazquez2022TPSAB1; the full causal chain is unproven; competing non-MC CT degradation mechanisms exist. _Motivated by:_ patient-reported hypermobility improvement on mast cell-directed therapy and the recognition that pharmaceutical IgE pathway modulation may inadvertently treat connective tissue pathology — an underexplored clinical observation warranting mechanistic investigation.

- *Narcolepsy Type 2 as ME/CFS Cross-Disease Metabolic Parallel — Orexin System Integration* ([Chapter 14d, new narcolepsy section `sec:narcolepsy-mecfs` with main speculation `@spec:mecfs-functional-narcolepsy` (cert 0.25$arrow$0.30 after 4c feed-in from hyp:ch15-orexin-suppression), `@spec:orexin-metabolic-canary` (cert 0.20), `@oq:csf-orexin-mecfs`, plus 30 brainstorm-derived environments (7 hypotheses cert 0.10--0.30, 5 cross-disease, 10 therapeutic, 3 math model, 10 diagnostic/biomarker); Chapter 15, orexin section updated with NT2 gray-zone cross-reference; Chapter 16, causal hierarchy sleep-architecture and sickness-behavior sections updated with orexin-suppression mechanism and narcolepsy cross-refs; Chapter 19, suvorexant/lemborexant entry updated with post-viral orexin evidence and DORA-in-orexin-deficiency caveat; Chapter 24, modafinil orexin mechanism updated with functional narcolepsy cross-ref; Chapter 26, L-carnitine CPT bypass certainty 0.30$arrow$0.35 via two independent orexin-FAO convergence lines; Appendix H, new section `sec:bib-narcolepsy-orexin` with 5 annotated entries; bib/sleep.bib, 5 new entries (@Constantinescu2011orexinMSnull cert 0.70, @Dauvilliers2011painNarcolepsy cert 0.65, @Nardone2011corticalEDS cert 0.65, @Horiuchi2015carnitineOrexin cert 0.55, @Lopez2023tcellNarcolepsy cert 0.65); hypothesis registry, 45 new entries (2 main + 30 brainstorm + 1 missing OQ added in review + 12 research/biomarker); Phase 4a falsifiability: all environments include falsifiable predictions and "Falsified if" clauses; Phase 4b retrospective adaptation: 12 matches examined, 5 adapted (5 reinforced, 0 contradicted, 0 ambiguous, 7 deferred), 0 certainty bumps; Phase 4c cross-hypothesis compatibility: 68 pairs audited (32 reinforcement, 22 feed-into, 6 conflict, 8 independent), 6 reinforcement chains (longest 4 hops), 4 conflict clusters, 3 certainty bumps (functional-narcolepsy 0.25$arrow$0.30, L-carnitine 0.30$arrow$0.35), 2 reductions (epiphenomenon 0.20$arrow$0.15, phase-shift 0.30$arrow$0.25); Phase 6 review: 6a convergence 2 rounds (2 findings fixed: missing registry entry, indentation), 6b adversarial 3 personas 14 findings (2 critical fixed: rodent qualifier, DORA caveat)]): Integrated narcolepsy Type 2 (NT2, without cataplexy) as cross-disease parallel for ME/CFS. Core hypothesis: chronic neuroinflammation functionally suppresses orexin neuron activity via neurotensin interneurons, producing an acquired NT2-like state with intermediate orexin levels (110--200 pg/mL gray zone) without autoimmune destruction. Key evidence: animal models demonstrate cytokine$arrow$orexin suppression is causal (chemogenetic rescue reverses lethargy @Grossberg2011orexinLethargy), plasma orexin-A reduced in post-COVID fatigue @Ruhrländer2025orexinPASC @Heinicke2025orexinCOVID, but MS null @Constantinescu2011orexinMSnull and autoantibody null @Germain2025autoantibody constrain generalizability. Critical missing evidence: no CSF orexin-A measurement in ME/CFS. Metabolic bridge via CPT1B/carnitine links orexin neuron vulnerability to ME/CFS bioenergetic dysfunction @Horiuchi2015carnitineOrexin. _Motivated by:_ Grossberg et al.\ 2011 @Grossberg2011orexinLethargy --- established causal circuit from cytokines to orexin suppression to lethargy in animal models; López-Amador 2025 @LopezAmador2025orexin --- integrative review documenting reduced orexin-A across 27 ME/CFS-relevant studies.

- *Weight Management in ME/CFS — Practical Strategies When Movement Is Impossible or Severely Limited* ([Chapter 26, new `== Weight Management in ME/CFS` section `sec:weight-management` with `@cf:caloric-needs-severity` clinical finding (severity-stratified caloric targets, cert 0.45), `@warn:caloric-restriction-severe` warning (caloric restriction contraindicated in moderate-to-severe), `@spec:hypometabolic-caloric-recalibration` speculation (cert 0.35), `@hyp:overfeeding-paradox` hypothesis (cert 0.55), `@oq:ree-mecfs-severity` open question, `@oq:weight-loss-symptom-improvement` open question, `@spec:mct-fat-oxidation-bypass` speculation (cert 0.40), `@spec:pem-phase-metabolic-protection` speculation (cert 0.35), `@spec:pem-insulin-resistance-weight` speculation (cert 0.35), `@spec:glp1-microdosing` speculation (cert 0.30), `@spec:nmes-weight-management` speculation (cert 0.45); Chapter 3, expanded weight changes subsection with SCI caloric overestimation evidence and overfeeding paradox cross-reference; references.bib, 16 new entries with `research_stream = weight-management-mecfs`; Appendix H, 8 new annotated bibliography entries in new `== Weight Management in ME/CFS` section; hypothesis registry, 4 new entries (1H, 1S, 2OQ); hypothesis tree subtree `weight-management-mecfs` with 40 nodes (9 integrated)]): Standard weight management (exercise + caloric restriction) is contraindicated in ME/CFS. The SCI literature provides the closest metabolic analog: predictive equations overestimate RMR by 5–32% in immobile populations @Alazzam2023SCI, and positive energy balance during bed rest accelerates muscle atrophy @Biolo2008BedRest. Key new principle: body composition optimization (lean mass preservation) supersedes scale weight. Protein target elevated to 1.5–2.0 g/kg IBW during any weight management intervention @Weijs2025Protein. GLP-1 RAs produce 25–60% lean mass loss @Neeland2024LeanMass — microdosing protocol proposed as safer alternative. Critical evidence gap: zero ME/CFS REE studies by indirect calorimetry exist. _Motivated by:_ Alazzam 2023 @Alazzam2023SCI — SCI metabolic rate overestimation as ME/CFS analog; Biolo 2008 @Biolo2008BedRest — positive energy balance worsens muscle atrophy during immobility.

- *DecodeME-Verifiable Hypotheses: Computable Analyses Using Existing Genotype + Phenotype Data* ([Chapter 12, new `==== Computable Analyses Using Existing DecodeME Data` section `sec:decodeme-computable` with 8 hypotheses: sex-differential architecture `@hyp:sex-differential-architecture` (cert 0.55), PRS severity dose-response `@hyp:prs-severity-dose-response` (cert 0.60), genotype-trigger interaction `@hyp:genotype-trigger-interaction` (cert 0.45), non-infectious higher loading `@hyp:non-infectious-higher-loading` (cert 0.50), depression comorbidity genetic `@hyp:depression-comorbidity-genetic` (cert 0.60), heritability partitioning `@hyp:heritability-partitioning-brain` (cert 0.65), partitioned rg IBS `@hyp:partitioned-rg-ibs` (cert 0.55), diagnostic criteria genetic `@hyp:diagnostic-criteria-genetic` (cert 0.45), Long COVID shared genes `@hyp:long-covid-shared-genes` (cert 0.50); 3 speculations: amitriptyline pharmacogenomics `@spec:amitriptyline-pharmacogenomics` (cert 0.50), between-cluster epistasis `@spec:between-cluster-epistasis` (cert 0.40), external PRS symptom modifiers `@spec:external-prs-symptom-modifiers` (cert 0.50); 7 open questions: X chromosome `@oq:x-chromosome-mecfs`, severe subgroup GWAS `@oq:severe-subgroup-gwas`, MR programme `@oq:mendelian-randomisation-programme`, ADHD/FM correlations `@oq:adhd-fm-genetic-correlations`, PRS vs family history `@oq:prs-vs-family-history`, PheWAS `@oq:phewas-decodeme-loci`, onset age quantitative GWAS `@oq:onset-age-quantitative-gwas`; hypothesis registry, 13 new entries (8H, 3S, 2P); hypothesis tree subtree `decodeme-verifiable` with 25 nodes]): All 25 analyses are computable from existing DecodeME data (n=17,000+ genotyped with severity, diagnostic criteria, infection typing, depression comorbidity, amitriptyline use, family history, sex) plus publicly available external GWAS summary statistics --- no new recruitment or genotyping required. Top-3 priority analyses: (1) bidirectional Mendelian randomisation