ent); Phase 6: content review 2 findings (1 fixed), adversarial 7 findings (7 fixed, 3 ambiguities flagged), typst 9 findings (9 fixed); 2 opportunistic fixes (bidirectional serotonin xref, medications-systems→medications-mechanisms)]): Integrated 12 new POTS papers with four key findings reshaping the paper's understanding of POTS in ME/CFS: (1) tachycardia is compensatory — ivabradine/beta-blockers risk worsening CBF in low-SV patients, requiring pre-treatment SV stratification (Marchetta 2025, Chopra 2026, Miranda-Hurtado 2026); (2) cerebral blood flow, not heart rate, is the central mediator of POTS symptoms — the SV→ETCO2→CBF pathway explains orthostatic brain fog via hypocapnic vasoconstriction amplified beyond simple perfusion pressure deficits, and chronic repeated CBF drops produce cumulative structural brain changes (Malik 2026 gray matter atrophy, Seeley 2025 regional SPECT hypoperfusion); (3) POTS has a substantial CNS amplification component — 67% meet central sensitization criteria (Mathew 2026, Novak lab), reframing POTS as partly a disorder of autonomic interoception; (4) the diagnostic threshold has poor reproducibility (Hedge 2026), but day-to-day HR increment variability may be diagnostic information rather than nuisance noise — an "autonomic stability index" distinguishing structurally fixed from dynamically unstable autonomic circuits. _Motivated by:_ @vanCampen2024twoHemodynamic — first characterization of two distinct hemodynamic POTS subtypes specifically in ME/CFS patients; @MirandaHurtado2026CBFpots — establishing the SV→ETCO2→CBF mechanistic pathway (Raj lab); @Mathew2026centralSens — 67% central sensitization prevalence in POTS (JAMA Netw Open).

