- *Post-exercise recovery optimization integration* ([Chapter 26, new `sec:post-exercise-recovery` section with 9 subsections: recovery failure contrast `sec:recovery-failure-contrast`, PEM decomposition `sec:pem-decomposition`, active recovery contraindication `sec:active-recovery-contraindication`, passive recovery modalities `sec:passive-recovery`, intercepting PEM inflammation `sec:intercepting-pem-inflammation`, post-exercise nutrition `sec:post-exercise-nutrition`, timing protocol `sec:exercise-timing-protocol`, muscle mass and recovery `sec:muscle-mass-recovery`, GET debate `sec:get-debate-recovery`, severity-stratified protocols `sec:severity-recovery-protocols`; 4 speculation environments: `spec:recovery-network-collapse` (cert 0.40), `spec:thermal-exercise-mimetic` (cert 0.35), `spec:resolution-failure-pem` (cert 0.45), `spec:antihistamine-pem-blockade` (cert 0.40); 2 warning environments: `warn:active-recovery-contraindicated`, `warn:get-harm-mecfs`; 1 practical warning: `warn:massage-severity-gating`; 1 protocol: `protocol:recovery-timing`; exercise-pem.bib, 5 new entries; treatments.bib, 2 new entries; Appendix H, 14 annotated entries]): Comprehensive integration of post-exercise recovery science contrasted with ME/CFS recovery failure. Core framework: normal recovery requires PGC-1alpha/AMPK/SIRT1 axis for mitochondrial biogenesis + HSP70 for protein repair + sleep for GH-mediated tissue repair --- all broken in ME/CFS, creating a network-level collapse rather than single-pathway failure. Key additions: active recovery (décrassage) explicitly contraindicated with mechanistic rationale (ATP cost, NAD+ diversion, membrane depolarization extension @Jammes2020MembranePotential); PEM decomposed into cognitive (noradrenergic @Aregawi2026Noradrenergic + neuroinflammatory), muscular (mitochondrial + membrane @Jammes2020MembranePotential + lactate @Lien2019LactateAbnormal), and autonomic (vascular @Wirth2023) components --- partial relief of cognitive PEM is a legitimate clinical goal; resolution failure hypothesis (PEM persists because SPM-mediated inflammation resolution is broken, not because inflammation is excessive); pre-emptive antihistamine protocol (H1+H2 blockade before exercise to prevent mast-cell-mediated cerebral hypoperfusion @Rohrhofer2025mecfsmast); infrared sauna/Waon therapy as passive exercise mimetic bypassing ATP cost (@Soejima2015WaonTherapyCFS, @Munemoto2017Waon); massage meta-analysis integrated with severity-gated application warning (@Li2024MassageMeta); complete pre/during/post timing protocol for supplements and medications; muscle mass paradox (buffer vs metabolic liability); GET debate with both sides (White2023 vs Vink2025) and mechanistic argument for why training through PEM fails; severity-stratified recovery protocols (mild/moderate/severe). Phase 4a: 8 environments audited, 4 fully falsifiable, 1 weakly→fixed. Phase 4b: 43 matches examined, 2 reinforcements (ch06 NKA + ch17 ion channels), 0 contradictions. Phase 4c: 10 pairs audited, 3 reinforcement, 2 feed-into, 0 conflict. _Motivated by:_ @Jammes2020MembranePotential --- muscle membrane depolarization and redox subgroups provide direct evidence for differential recovery needs; @Lien2019LactateAbnormal --- abnormal lactate accumulation on repeated CPET demonstrates impaired metabolic recovery capacity; @Li2024MassageMeta --- first systematic evidence for massage in CFS, requiring severity-gated interpretation for ME/CFS.

- *Fitness-Maintenance Conceptual Framework integration* ([Chapter 17, expanded section with 2 new speculations: COPD/HF cross-disease maintenance protocols `@spec:cross-disease-maintenance` (cert 0.50), bifurcation model of exercise dose-response `@spec:bifurcation-model` (cert 0.40); Chapter 14, 1 reinforcement edit correcting "improve cardiovascular fitness" to "maintain cardiovascular function" with cross-ref to `@subsec:fitness-maintenance`; hypothesis registry, 6 new entries]): Formalized the conceptual distinction between fitness maintenance (preventing further loss) and fitness improvement (building capacity) in ME/CFS, anchored in energy envelope theory @Jason2008EnergyEnvelope and 2-day CPET evidence @keller2024cpet.

- *CPET null replication — Mancini/Natelson 2026 integration* ([Chapter 17, new limitation block on contested 2-day CPET evidence, revised `@hyp:fitness-maintenance-distinction` cert 0.60→0.55 with CPET-specific support reduced, revised `@spec:bifurcation-model` to note contested group-average decline, revised GET harms section to note null replication; Chapter 14f, revised `@hyp:cpet-2-deterioration-signature` cert 0.60→0.55, expanded limitation block with null replication details; hypothesis registry, 2 entries updated (fitness-maintenance-distinction 0.60→0.55, bifurcation model); references.bib, 1 new entry (@Mancini2026CPET); Appendix H, 1 new annotated entry]): Mancini, Natelson et al. (2026, Front. Physiol., NIH-funded NS117638, n=58 ME/CFS Fukuda criteria + 25 sedentary controls) found no significant Day 1→Day 2 group-average decline in peak VO₂ or VO₂ at VT, contradicting Keller et al. 2024 (n=84+71 CCC, 5--8% declines). Both studies concur that ME/CFS patients have elevated Borg RPE at all workloads and lower maximal HR (chronotropic incompetence). Methodological differences that may explain the divergence: patient criteria (CCC stricter vs. Fukuda broader), max-effort enforcement (Keller included Day 2 CRI failures as PEM; Mancini excluded non-ACSM-compliant tests), COI status (Keller group offers CPET on fee-for-service basis). The fitness-maintenance framework was re-anchored to energy envelope theory, patient-reported GET harms, and the consistent finding of elevated RPE across all CPET studies — none of which depend on whether group-average VO₂ decline replicates. Certainty reductions are conservative and documented with incoming evidence certainty. _Motivated by:_ @Mancini2026CPET — first NIH-funded null replication of 2-day CPET in ME/CFS from a senior investigator (Natelson, Icahn/Mount Sinai), directly challenging the CPET evidence base underpinning the fitness-maintenance-distinction hypothesis.t 0.60, `@spec:adl-stability-metric` cert 0.35, `@spec:fitness-acceptance` cert 0.20) during the parent `exercise-modality-expansion` cycle. This dedicated cycle added two extensions: (1) a cross-disease analogy from COPD and heart failure rehabilitation, where maintenance-phase protocols are standard in diseases with pathophysiological exercise intolerance, providing a transferable protocol architecture; (2) a mathematical bifurcation model formalizing the PEM threshold as a sign-flip point where dF/dt changes from maintenance (net benefit) to deterioration (net harm). Phase 4a falsifiability audit tightened prediction specifications for 3 environments. Phase 4b retrospective adaptation corrected one pre-existing "improve fitness" framing in ch14-symptom-management. _Motivated by:_ @keller2024cpet — demonstrates exercise produces physiological deterioration, not training adaptation; @Jason2008EnergyEnvelope — defines the safe operating range; @Charlton2026pem — counters deconditioning model in British Journal of Sports Medicine.

- *Engineered exosomes reverse sleep deprivation brain damage — ME/CFS integration* ([Chapter 8, new `spec:engineered-exosome-bbb-mrna` speculation (cert 0.55) on RVG-targeted exosome HSP70 mRNA delivery across BBB; Chapter 7, new `spec:exosome-biogenesis-impairment` speculation (cert 0.25) on impaired exosome biogenesis as chronicity contributor; Chapter 18, new `spec:engineered-exosome-bbb-mrna` (cert 0.30), `spec:hsp70-inducers` (cert 0.45) and `spec:pparg-exosome-uptake` (cert 0.20) speculations + 1 open-question on tVNS-enhanced delivery; Chapter 20, new `spec:exosome-biomarker-panel` (cert 0.35) and `spec:exosomal-hsp70-biomarker` (cert 0.35) on brain-derived exosome biomarkers; Chapter 25, new glymphatic reversibility note linking Kang et al. to sleep neuroprotection rationale; Chapter 25b, new preclinical study programme (4 studies: iPSC cargo screening, chronic neuroinflammation BBB trafficking, repeated dosing immunogenicity, circadian timing); Appendix H, new annotated bib section `sec:bib-exosome-sleep-reversal` (3 entries); references.bib, 3 new entries (@Kang2026ExosomeHSP70Sleep cert 0.55,  cert 0.70,  cert 0.70); hypothesis registry, 2 new entries]): Kang et al. (2026, Translational Psychiatry) demonstrated that RVG-targeted engineered exosomes carrying HSP70 mRNA cross the BBB and completely reverse cognitive deficits and hippocampal neuroinflammation in sleep-deprived mice — reducing TNF-α, IL-6, IL-1β while increasing IL-10, BDNF, and pCREB. This is the first demonstration that engineered exosomes can deliver functional mRNA cargo (not siRNA/miRNA) to CNS targets, establishing proof-of-principle that the BBB is tractable to exosome-mediated mRNA therapy. Three integration threads: (1) therapeutic — engineered exosomes could address the BBB delivery bottleneck that limits pharmacological approaches to ME/CFS neuroinflammation, though manufacturing standardisation, immunogenicity, and CNS delivery fraction (less than 1 percent of injected dose) are substantial barriers; (2) biomarker — brain-derived exosomes (captured via L1CAM/GFAP/TMEM119 immunoprecipitation) could provide a peripheral blood window into compartmentalised CNS pathology invisible to standard assays, with HSP70 and inflammatory cytokine cargo as candidate analytes; (3) pathophysiology — if endogenous exosome biogenesis is impaired in ME/CFS (ESCRT dysfunction, ATP depletion), this creates a dual problem of impaired intercellular signalling AND reduced therapeutic exosome efficacy in chronic disease. Phase 4b (retrospective adaptation): BBB vulnerability hypothesis bumped 0.35→0.40, endothelial ApoExos speculation bumped 0.35→0.40 (both reinforced by Kang et al. demonstration of EV BBB delivery). Phase 4c (compatibility audit): 16 pairs across 9 registry hypotheses — 5 reinforcement, 3 feed-into chains, 1 tension flagged (HSAT2-exosome vs biogenesis impairment). All 7 new environments passed falsifiability audit (Phase 4a). _Motivated by:_ @Kang2026ExosomeHSP70Sleep — first demonstration that engineered exosomes delivering mRNA across BBB can reverse neuroinflammation and cognitive deficits caused by sleep loss;  — systematic review of EV BBB crossing mechanisms;  — comprehensive review of exosomes as brain-targeted nucleic acid delivery vehicles.

- *Exercise modality expansion integration* ([Chapter 17, new/expanded sections: constant body position hypothesis `@hyp:constant-body-position` (cert 0.50), aquatic exercise & hydrostatic pressure speculation `@spec:aquatic-hydrostatic` (cert 0.68), thermoneutral water prerequisite `@spec:thermoneutral-water` (cert 0.55), water rowing protocol `@spec:water-rowing` (cert 0.30), adapted swimming protocol (backstroke/no turns) `@spec:adapted-swimming` (cert 0.35), resistance band HR speculation `@spec:resistance-band-hr` (cert 0.40), modality safety classification taxonomy `@spec:modality-classification` (cert 0.55), post-exercise horizontal rest `@spec:post-exercise-horizontal-rest` (cert 0.55), compound vs. isolated movement HR hypothesis `@hyp:compound-vs-isolated-hr` (cert 0.40); hypothesis registry, 9 new entries; references.bib, 2 new entries (Schmid2007WaterImmersion, Hanna1993WaterImmersion); Appendix H, 2 new annotated entries]): Expanded Ch. 17 Safe Movement Approaches with modality-by-modality guidance for exercise in ME/CFS/POTS, anchored to the patient-observed constant-body-position safety principle. Key findings: water immersion (chest-deep, thermoneutral 32°C) produces parasympathetic shift via hydrostatic pressure augmentation of venous return — a mechanism distinct from buoyancy alone — but may fail to benefit patients with autonomic/cardiac impairment in upright positions (Hanna 1993). Thermoneutral temperature (31–32°C) is safety-critical: cold triggers sympathetic activation, warm triggers vasodilation/hypotension in POTS. Proposed novel modalities: water rowing (combines constant position + hydrostatic pressure + compound movement distribution), adapted backstroke swimming (face always out of water, no turns, no Valsalva), and seated/supine resistance bands with very slow tempo (5-2-5) for hEDS/ME/CFS comorbidity. Five-tier orthostatic-demand taxonomy for modality selection by severity. Post-exercise horizontal rest extends Klimas program's supine-rest principle to all modalities. Compound vs. isolated movement hypothesis: in ME/CFS with global hypoperfusion, compound movements may elicit lower HR than isolated movements at matched intensity, inverting the healthy-population pattern. Phase 4b (retrospective adaptation): "Pool exercises" line updated with Schmid citation + cross-refs. Phase 4c (compatibility audit): 135 pairs examined across 9 new × 15 existing mechanisms — zero conflicts, 18 reinforcement pairs, 27 feed-into chains (longest: 5 elements — hydrostatic → parasympathetic shift → reduced orthostatic demand → improved cerebral perfusion → reduced PEM). All 9 environments passed falsifiability audit (Phase 4a). _Motivated by:_ @Schmid2007WaterImmersion — chest-deep thermoneutral water immersion physiologically validated as parasympathetic activator in cardiac populations; @Hanna1993WaterImmersion — demonstrates that autonomic/cardiac impairment attenuates hydrostatic preload benefit during upright exercise, informing position-specific recommendations.
 ([Chapter 1, 2 reinforcement citation edits; Chapter 5 onset-patterns, 1 new research implication (female predominance parity); Chapter 5 subgroups, 1 new cross-reference; Chapter 7 immune, 1 new hypothesis environment (IM three-compartment failure cert 0.40); Chapter 14d cross-disease, 3 new speculation environments (Hodgkin lymphoma bridge cert 0.20, T1D pubertal thymic bridge cert 0.20, XCI escape gender paradox cert 0.30); Chapter 16 supplements, 3 new speculation environments (zinc-thymulin 0.25, NAD+ precursors late-onset 0.25, melatonin thymic 0.25); Chapter 25b proposed studies, 1 new open-question (DecodeME stratified GWAS); hypothesis registry, 8 new entries]): McGrath et al. (2026) confirmed bimodal ME/CFS onset age in European survey (n=9,380) and DecodeME (n=6,455) with peaks at ~16 and ~37 and clinically meaningful differences (early: higher severity OR 2.15, IM enrichment OR 2.32, familial clustering OR 1.43; late: lower severity, less infectious trigger dominance). Constant ~80% female ratio across both peaks motivated non-hormonal XCI-escape susceptibility hypothesis. Existing ch05 and ch14d content was already partially integrated (2026-04-16) but lacked hypothesis registry entries. This cycle added 8 registry entries, 3 cross-disease bridge speculations, IM three-compartment immune failure hypothesis, 3 onset-age-stratified supplement proposals, DecodeME stratified GWAS, female predominance parity cross-reference, and McGrath reinforcement citations to ch01. _Motivated by:_ @McGrath2026bimodalOnset — first large-scale multi-country confirmation of bimodal onset age with clinical correlates; @Bakken2014bimodalOnset — original Norwegian registry finding; @Jin2019vitiligoBimodal — vitiligo precedent demonstrating bimodal onset can reveal distinct genetic architectures.

- *Connective tissue disorders full integration* ([Chapter 6, 3 new environments: HIF-1alpha-Mito-ECM triad hypothesis, ARB capillary restoration hypothesis, fibroblast glycogen speculation; Chapter 7, 7 new environments: mechanical-stress mast cell threshold, vagal-mast cell-CT axis, matrix stiffness-mast cell priming cycle, ECM fragment autoantigen, tendinopathy-ME/CFS HIF-1alpha parallel, ECM inflammatory priming hypothesis, gut microbiome-ECM axis; Chapter 8, 5 new environments: glymphatic-capillary clearance hypothesis, post-infectious acquired Chiari speculation, BM-glymphatic bidirectional hypothesis, proprioceptive fatigue-CCI, cervical sympathetic ganglion compression; Chapter 10, 2 new environments: structural vs functional OI stratification hypothesis, tVNS for structural-autonomic dysfunction; Chapter 11, 2 new speculations: gut microbiome-ECM triad, ECM fragment-microbiome bidirectional; Chapter 12, 3 new speculations: LOX deficiency, miRNA-mediated ECM regulation, crosslink enzyme polymorphisms; Chapter 13, 7 new environments: HIF-1alpha-Mito-ECM triad hypothesis, systemic tendinopathy speculation, diabetic BM thickening parallel, Marfan-CCI parallel, scleroderma ECM parallel, Alzheimer-MMP parallel, tendinopathy-HIF-1alpha parallel; Chapter 15, 5 new environments: post-exertional MMP surge hypothesis, Piezo channel-mast cell mechanosensing, autonomic nerve-ECM signaling, tendon phenotype, autonomic-vasomotor ECM dysregulation; Chapter 16, 7 new supplement proposals in "Connective Tissue Support" section: collagen peptides+vitamin C, copper+P5P, vitamin D ECM regulation, benfotiamine, vitamin K2 MGP, hyaluronan, circadian ascorbic acid+AKG; Chapter 17, 6 new non-pharm interventions: glymphatic clearance enhancement, circadian collagen resynchronization, neutral zone cervical positioning, endurance-focused cervical training, optimal sleep positioning, progressive cervical overload; Chapter 18, 3 new emerging therapies: tVNS for mast cell-ECM modulation, HIF isoform rebalancing, TGF-beta1 blockade; Chapter 19, 3 new integrative protocols: dual mast cell-MMP inhibition, timed collagen cofactor protocol, CCI multi-modal management; Chapter 20, 6 new biomarker speculations in "Connective Tissue and ECM Biomarkers" section; Chapter 25b, 4 new proposed studies; Chapter 27, 2 math model proposals; Chapter 28, mast cell-ECM bistable model; Chapter 30, multi-compartment ECM turnover model + HIF-1alpha-Mito-ECM triad cross-ref; Chapter 31, ECM degradation temporal trajectory speculation; Chapter 32, sigmoid CCI-orthostatic model; hypothesis-registry.typ, 48 new entries]): Comprehensive expansion of prior limited CTD integration — all 64 brainstorm ideas now integrated across 20 chapter files. Core framework: HIF-1alpha-mitochondria-ECM self-reinforcing triad as unifying mechanism producing connective tissue pathology, mast cell-MMP positive feedback creating bistable degraded states, basement membrane thickening impairing both perfusion and glymphatic clearance, and structural-vs-functional orthostatic intolerance stratification for treatment selection. Key additions: post-exertional MMP surge as PEM amplifier, glymphatic-capillary bidirectional impairment, circadian collagen synthesis optimization, CCI progressive overload pacing protocol, multi-compartment ECM turnover model, sigmoid CCI-orthostatic severity model. Prior changelog entry (May 13) covered only 2 hypotheses + 10 papers; this pass completes the full pipeline for the topic. _Motivated by:_ @Wirth2026CTDMECFS — bidirectional CTD-ME/CFS relationship proposing ROS-prolyl hydroxylase-HIF-1alpha-mast cell pathway; @Moschini2026HIFTendinopathy — HIF-1alpha drives connective tissue pathology independently of VEGF; @Wust2024capillary — capillary basement membrane thickening in ME/CFS muscle; @Bragee2020 — 80% CCI prevalence in ME/CFS; @Magadmi2019 — CADM1 mast cell-neuron adhesion mechanism.

- *Methylation loss as consolidation mechanism integration* ([Chapter 16, new `spec:methylation-loss-consolidation` speculation (0.45/0.30/0.20 certainty) and `spec:icf-methylation-parallel` speculation (0.65/0.35) with ICF syndrome as Mendelian proof of methylation-loss immune pathology; Chapter 33, new `oq:consolidation-directionality` open-question (0.55/0.30) flagging cal(M) directionality ambiguity; Chapter 14, updated `oq:epigenetic-gap` with bidirectional evidence and remethylation strategies; Chapter 31, added loss-model cross-reference; Chapter 32, softened "deepened by methylation" to accommodate gain or loss; references.bib, 3 new entries (Pappalardo2021repeats, Peppercorn2025methylation, BonnetFourel2026ProAB)]): The paper's epigenetic consolidation model defined consolidation as gain of methylation (DNMT3A/3B-driven) with demethylation as reversal. The actual ME/CFS evidence is bidirectional — PTPRN2 hypomethylation (Chalder/Moreau 2026), pericentromeric hypomethylation → HSAT2 derepression, global methylation loss across multiple EWAS cohorts — while RRBS of PBMCs shows hypermethylation dominates (Peppercorn 2025, n=5). Integration adds bidirectional framing: the consolidation variable cal(M) may oversimplify if treated as scalar; a vector tracking per-locus methylation direction would be more faithful. ICF syndrome (DNMT3B mutations → pericentromeric hypomethylation → immune deficiency) provides Mendelian proof that methylation loss alone causes immune pathology. Treatment directionality matters: remethylation strategies (DNMT3A activators, SAMe, methyl-folate, betaine) are the safer default vs demethylating agents (risk of worsening existing hypomethylation). Phase 4b retrospective adaptation: 5 references examined in modeling chapters; 3 adapted with directional qualifiers. _Motivated by:_ Geneviève Fourel (personal communication, May 2026) proposing that consolidation = loss of DNA methylation; @BonnetFourel2026ProAB — ProA/ProB repeat sequence framework showing CpG methylation loss disproportionately impacts ProB RepSeqs (satellites, young LINE-1s, ERVs), weakening the B/heterochromatin compartment, with DNMT3B redistribution as the driver of methylation erosion; @ChalderMoreau2026ptprn2 — PTPRN2 hypomethylation survives correction and correlates with symptoms; @Peppercorn2025methylation — RRBS evidence of bidirectional methylation with hypermethylation dominant in PBMCs; @Pappalardo2021repeats — ICF syndrome as Mendelian proof-of-concept.

- *pDC dysfunction and post-viral migration hijack integration* ([Chapter 7, expanded pDC temporal dynamics speculation with "pDC desert" concept (19/23 studies) and blood→tissue migration hijack model (CXCR3/CXCL9-11), new open-question environment (pDC functional assays); Chapter 14d, pDC caveat added to Sjögren's cross-disease section with blood↓/tissue↑ compartment artefact clarification; Chapter 17, dendritic cell universal mechanisms entry expanded with conserved post-viral/autoimmune pattern and chemokine migration mechanism; Appendix H, new "pDC Dysfunction and Post-Viral Biology" section with 3 annotated entries; references.bib, 3 new entries]): Child cycle of NET/DNase integration focused on resolving the pDC directionality contradiction between Garcia 2024 (blood depletion) and Augustin 2026 (gut tissue expansion). Phase 1 found 3 papers: Van der Sluis 2022 (Cell Reports review of 23 studies — 19/23 show blood pDC depletion proportional to severity, "pDC desert" concept), Li 2017 (Frontiers in Immunology — blood↓/tissue↑ pattern conserved across SLE/RA/psoriasis/cancer via CXCR3/CXCL9-11 and CXCR4/CXCL12), and Pérez-Gómez 2021 (Cellular & Molecular Immunology — pDC deficiency persists 7 months post-COVID in both hospitalised and non-hospitalised patients). Integration established blood→tissue migration hijack as most parsimonious resolution with chemokine mechanism and persistent depletion timeline. Key finding: pDC depletion is not COVID-19-specific but a conserved post-viral/autoimmune phenomenon creating dual deficit (systemic DNase1L3 deficiency + tissue-localised IFN-α-driven inflammation). Clinical implications remain at research stage — no pDC-directed therapeutics tested in ME/CFS. _Motivated by:_ @VanderSluis2022pDCcovid — "pDC desert" concept unifying pDC depletion findings across 19/23 COVID-19 studies; @Li2017pDCdisease — blood→tissue migration pattern as established phenomenon across autoimmune diseases; @PerezGomez2021pDCpersist — persistent pDC depletion at 7 months challenging simple temporal recovery models.

- *NET/DNase imbalance in post-viral conditions integration* ([Chapter 7, expanded Garcia et al. anchor paper integration (n=145, certainty 0.70) with two-mechanism framework (pDC depletion + DNASE1 polymorphisms), 4 new speculation environments, 1 new hypothesis environment; Chapter 6, 2 new speculation environments (insulin resistance as bidirectional MET-NETosis driver, exercise-induced NETosis as PEM amplifier) and 1 reinforcement edit; Chapter 12, new DNASE1/DNASE1L3 susceptibility loci section; Chapter 17, universal mechanisms neutrophil dysfunction entry updated; Chapter 18, new "NET-Targeting Therapies" section with 4 speculation environments (DNase I dornase alfa, PAD4 inhibition, metformin, NET-microclot targeting) covering treatment guidelines for severe patients; Chapter 20, new "NET Degradation and DNase Activity" biomarker section with 1 open-question; Appendix H, 6 new annotated entries; references.bib, 5 new entries + anchor paper reference corrected (journal, DOI, PMID fixed from erroneous Nature Communications to correct Journal of Translational Medicine); hypothesis-registry.typ updated; corrigendum entry for fixed reference]): Comprehensive integration of Garcia et al. (2024) J Transl Med study (PMC10919029) demonstrating NET/DNase imbalance as a severity driver in COVID-19 via pDC depletion and DNASE1 genetic polymorphisms, extended through 5 supplementary papers (Sanhueza 2026 insulin-NETosis, Thierry 2025 NET-microclot structure, Perez Mazzali 2026 early immune prediction, Augustin 2026 gut pDC expansion, Asaba 2026 cross-viral NET review). Anchor paper already partially integrated; this cycle deepened mechanistic detail (functional DNase assay, two upstream mechanisms, n/ml details), added cross-chapter connections (genetics, universal mechanisms, emerging therapies, biomarkers), and integrated 85 brainstorm ideas as 14 speculations/hypotheses/open-questions across 6 chapters. Key mechanistic findings: NET/DNase ratio (not NET production alone) drives severity; pDC migration hijack hypothesis (acute depletion → chronic tissue expansion) resolves directionality contradiction between Garcia and Augustin; insulin resistance establishes metabolic-immune NETosis loop; NETs structurally stabilise microclots. Clinical implications remain speculative — all therapeutic suggestions (DNase I, metformin, PAD4 inhibitors) carry 0.15–0.25 certainty ratings and explicit warnings. _Motivated by:_ @GarciaLabroucheColomer2024 — first demonstration of functional DNase deficiency, pDC depletion, and DNASE1 polymorphism-driven NET/DNase imbalance as COVID-19 severity mechanism with direct ME/CFS implications for post-viral thrombo-inflammatory pathology; @Sanhueza2026NETosisIR — de novo insulin resistance as metabolic NETosis driver creating energy-immune domain bridge; @Thierry2025MicroclotsNETs — NET-microclot structural association providing mechanism for persistent microvascular obstruction resistant to standard anticoagulation. ([Chapter 14b, new `sec:tissue-specific-autoantibodies` section with 6 environments (achievement, hypothesis, speculation, 2 open-questions); Chapter 14d, new autoantibody convergence section with 2 environments (hypothesis, open-question) and 2 cross-disease speculation environments (CIDAN, MS bridge); Chapter 7, reinforcement citation for IgM/failed class-switching content; Chapter 16, new immunomodulatory supplement section with 3 speculation environments; Chapter 17, new autonomic/immune section with 3 environments (2 speculations, 1 open-question); Chapter 18, new B-cell-targeted and autoantibody-modulating section with 6 environments; Chapter 28, 2 model extension environments (IgM class-switching ODE, PK/PD compartmental model); references.bib, 1 new entry; Appendix H, 1 new annotated entry; hypothesis-registry.typ, 4 new entries]): Integration of Tatai et al. (2026) GeroScience study applying simultaneous multi-tissue autoantibody screening to long COVID (n=114). Core findings: tissue-specific autoantibodies (cardiac 54 percent, vascular 34 percent, pulmonary 34 percent), IgM-dominated (60 percent vs 36 percent in controls), NOT detected by ANA HEp-2 testing, associated with neurovascular manifestations and persistent at 141-day follow-up with de novo emergence. Phase 2 added tissue-specific autoantibody section to Chapter 14b with dual-population (GPCR IgG vs tissue-structural IgM) framework bridging the isotype discrepancy; ANA HEp-2 diagnostic gap hypothesis; IgM/failed class-switching speculation reinforced by convergent long COVID evidence in Chapter 7. Phase 3 brainstorm generated 36 ideas across all 9 categories. Phase 4 integrated 20-plus ideas including BTK inhibition, complement C1s inhibition, low-dose IL-2, glycocalyx disruption hypothesis, viral-GPCR molecular mimicry, quercetin/curcumin/omega-3 supplement rationales, tVNS/intermittent fasting/hyperthermia interventions, CIDAN IgM neuropathy parallel, MS B-cell-endothelial axis bridge, and two mathematical model extensions (ODE class-switching model, compartmental PK/PD model). Phase 4b retroactive adaptation: 1 match examined, 1 reinforcement (IgM dominance in ch07 convergent evidence from BCR sequencing angle). Build verified with multiple syntax fixes (p-value and percent characters incompatible with Typst markup). _Motivated by:_ @Tatai2026TSAutoantibodies — first multi-tissue autoantibody screening in long COVID revealing IgM-dominant tissue-specific autoreactivity invisible to standard ANA testing; findings bridge the diagnostic gap between GPCR autoantibody literature and structural autoimmunity, with direct implications for ME/CFS biomarker development and therapeutic stratification.

- *SleepFM AI sleep prediction integration* ([Chapter 15, new "Cross-Modal Physiological Decoupling" section with 3 environments and "Decoupling-Targeted Interventions" subsection with 5 environments; Chapter 20, new "AI-Based Approaches Using Sleep Physiology" section with 2 environments; Chapter 25b, new proposed study with 3-phase protocol; references.bib, 7 new entries; Appendix H, 12 new annotated entries; hypothesis-registry.typ, 10 new entries]): Integration of Thapa et al. (2026) Nature Medicine presenting SleepFM, the first large-scale multimodal AI sleep foundation model (585K+ hours PSG, 65K participants) predicting 130+ health conditions from one night's sleep. Core finding: cross-modal physiological decoupling — "a brain that looks asleep but a heart that looks awake" — is the strongest disease predictor, providing large-scale validation for decoupling mechanisms already documented in ME/CFS (alpha-delta sleep, LC-NE oscillatory dysfunction, autonomic-sleep dissociation, glymphatic cascade decoupling, circadian desynchronisation). Chapter 15 added cross-modal decoupling framework mapping findings to each sleep domain with pharmacological (propranolol, clonidine, pregabalin, SAMe) and non-pharmacological (slow-paced breathing, temperature modulation, tVNS) coupling restoration strategies plus Kuramoto multi-oscillator phase-lock mathematical model. Chapter 20 added SleepFM as candidate diagnostic biomarker platform. Chapter 25b added proposed 3-phase validation study. Phase 3 brainstorm: 31 ideas. All integrated. _Motivated by:_ @Thapa2026sleepfm — first large-scale demonstration that cross-modal physiological coupling integrity during sleep predicts future disease; finding that "out of sync" body systems carry stronger predictive signal than any single modality, validating the decoupling framework unifying ME/CFS sleep pathology. ([Chapter 13, new "Unified Post-Infectious Model" and "Historical Arc" sections with 4 environments; Chapter 6, new section with 3 environments (ATG13 hypothesis, SMPDL3B speculation, haptoglobin speculation); Chapter 7, new sections on fibronectin-IgG CICs and abortive viral reactivation framework with 3 environments; Chapter 14d, new cross-disease sections on Long-COVID counterfactual and immune reprogramming with 3 environments; references.bib, 1 new entry; Appendix H, 1 new annotated entry; hypothesis-registry.typ, 6 new entries]): Comprehensive integration of Watton & Prusty (2026) review proposing ME/CFS as a disorder of impaired physiological resilience within post-infectious disease biology. Core contribution: unified model centering on state-dependent pathology — cellular and vascular systems appear normal at rest but fail under physiological stress. Added unified post-infectious model section to Chapter 13 with environment documenting mechanistic convergence across immune, vascular, metabolic, and virological domains. Added historical arc section tracing PACE trial → FOI tribunal → 2021 NICE reversal; Long-COVID as counterfactual validation. Added novel mechanisms: ATG13 as circulating DAMP and autophagy/mitophagy dysregulation, SMPDL3B lipid raft-mitochondrial quality control bridge, haptoglobin proteoforms in PEM oxidative stress (Chapter 6); fibronectin-IgG CIC dysregulation with homeostatic antibody depletion, abortive viral reactivation framework extending beyond herpesviruses (Chapter 7); Long-COVID counterfactual validation, post-infectious disease spectrum model, selective immune cell reprogramming (Chapter 14d). Phase 3 brainstorm generated 52 ideas across all 9 categories. Phase 5 build verified (one label fix required). _Motivated by:_ @Watton2026unified — Article in Press review reframing ME/CFS as a disorder of impaired physiological resilience; authored by Watton (independent) & Prusty (Riga Stradiņš University, core ME/CFS HHV-6/mitochondrial researcher); integrates historical analysis with contemporary biological models; preprint caveat applied (certainty 0.55 re